<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Economy Surges at 5.6 Percent Rate in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. economic growth exploded
at an annual rate of 5.6 percent in the first quarter, the
strongest in a decade, according to initial estimates released by
the U.S. Commerce Department today.
</P>
<P>
U.S. economic growth in the fourth quarter of last year was a
robust 3.8 percent. The 5.6 percent surge in the first quarter was
the most since the fourth quarter of 1987.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the surge was led by an increase of 6.4
percent in consumer spending, which amounts to two-thirds of the
gross domestic products (GDP). The pace was nearly doubled the
rate of 3.4 percent in the fourth quarter of last year and the
fastest since the first quarter of 1988.
</P>
<P>
Real nonresidential fixed investment increased 11.9 percent in
the first three months, compared with an increase of 5.5 percent
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
Exports of goods and services increased by 8.1 percent in the
first quarter compared with a surge of 25 percent in the last
quarter of 1996. But imports were up by 21.9 percent compared with
an increase of 3.3 percent in the final three months of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The government expenditure decreased by 3.5 percent and the real
change in business inventories added 29 billion dollars to the
first-quarter change in real GDP after subtracting 17 billion
dollars from the fourth-quarter change.
</P>
<P>
The gain in overall GDP translated into an increase of 96.1
billion dollars, bringing the economy's inflation-adjusted output
to an annual rate of 7.09 trillion dollars, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department report on the GDP, the sum of all goods
and services produced in the United States, not only showed
extremely strong economic growth in the country. It also provided
new evidence of inflation creeping higher.
</P>
<P>
A key inflation gauge tied to the GDP rose at a 2.7 percent
annual rate, the fastest in two years, following a 1.9 percent
rate in the fourth quarter, a four-year low.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to preempt inflation, the U.S. Federal Reserve
(Fed) raised short-term interest rates a quarter percentage point
on March 25. It is now widely expected that the U.S. Fed will make
a similar increase when its policy-makers next meet on May 20.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Commerce Department said that revised estimate of economic
growth in the first quarter based on more comprehensive data will
be issued next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
