<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Visit to China "Highly Fruitful": Leghari </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani President Farooq
Leghari has described his two-day visit to China as "satisfactory
and highly fruitful".
</P>
<P>
The President made the comment today during an interview with
the Pakistani media on board the special presidential plane,
according to the Associated Press of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Talking about increasing the bilateral trade between Pakistan
and China, Leghari said that currently the balance of payments was
tilted in favor of China. Efforts were underway to identify newer
Pakistani items to be exported to China, for which experts are
busy working out suggestions.
</P>
<P>
China was the largest and solidly-emerging economy and had much
to offer, Leghari said, adding that "we should make efforts to see
that our salable surplus is worthier and of fair standard. We must
go beyond cotton and rice and offer other commodities, in the
non-traditional fields."
</P>
<P>
The President said that China has gone for hi-tech
manufacturing, with established markets--even those of Europe-- as
its buyers.
</P>
<P>
"We must benefit from the vast experience of our friendly
country, with whom, our relations transcend normal formalities,"
said Leghari.
</P>
<P>
China, he said, had been helping Pakistan in the form of
technical know-how and expertise, infrastructure and defense
related collaboration.
</P>
<P>
"We will be happy to see Chinese investments on equity
partnership basis, in manufacturing with easy marketability and
profits," he said.
</P>
<P>
Leghari held separate meetings with China's business executives
and scholars earlier today in Beijing. "The response (from the
meeting) was positive and encouraging", said Leghari.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural research, irrigation and electronics manufacturing
were new fields of cooperation proposed by the two countries
during the visit, Leghari said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
