<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Adopts Plans to Reassure Consumers about Food Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission
announced plans on Wednesday for reforming its approach to food
safety in an effort to reassure consumers in the wake of the mad
cow disease crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Commission said it would set up a new food safety office,
reorganize its system for seeking scientific advice and strengthen
its inspection procedures.
</P>
<P>
"Recent experience has clearly demonstrated that food safety is
not only of concern to the consumer, but is also at the very root
of a proper functioning of the market," it said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
According to the plans, the Commission's food safety activities
would be grouped in a Food and Veterinary Office that will be set
up in Ireland, reporting to Consumer Affairs Commissioner Emma
Bonino.
</P>
<P>
The Commission pledged to seek advice on food safety from
eminent and fully independent scientists whose opinions and
working methods would be accessible to all interested parties.
</P>
<P>
The Commission's various scientific advisory committees will be
regrouped and coordinated by a Scientific Steering Committee.
</P>
<P>
The Commission said it would strengthen food control and
inspection procedures. It also promised to introduce formal audit
procedures assessing national control system.
</P>
<P>
The shake-up fulfills a pledge made by Commission President
Jacques Santer in February to the European Parliament, which was
conducting an inquiry into the EU's handling of the mad cow
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Th Commission on Wednesday also adopted a paper that aims to
launch a debate on how the EU should approach food regulation in
the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
