<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Leaves for Moscow to Push NATO-Russia Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright leaves here today for Moscow to push forward
the negotiations between the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) and Russia.
</P>
<P>
During the one-day stay in Moscow, Albright will meet Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov in attempt to remove differences
over an agreement that will set future relations between Russia
and NATO.
</P>
<P>
Both the alliance and Russia has indicated that they would like
sign the document in late May, over one month before NATO convenes
its special summit in Madrid on expansion into the Central and
Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Moscow demands the alliance make "absolute commitment" to
guarantee that it will not station nuclear weapons nor substantial
combat troops on the territories of the new members of NATO. The
alliance, led by the U.S., rejects the demand.
</P>
<P>
In Moscow , Primakov today restated Russia's demands for
guarantees that NATO will not move its military infrastructure
into the new NATO members.
</P>
<P>
Last week, testified before the Senate, Albright said that
the U.S. will make no compromise on this issue.
</P>
<P>
"All we have done and all we will do is....in the current and
foreseeable security environment, we have no plan, no need and no
intention to station nuclear weapons in the new member countries,
nor do we contemplate permanently stationing substantial combat
forces," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
