<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Wins Swaythling Cup For 12th Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 30 (Xinhua) -- China leveled the
world record held by Hungary as it beat France 3-1 to win its 12th
Swaythling Cup for the men's team top honor at the 44th World
Table Tennis Championships here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Double Olympic champion Liu Guoliang beat former world champion
Jean-Philippe Gatien, anchoring the defending champion squad to a
3-1 victory over France, which made history on Tuesday to enter
its first-ever world team final.
</P>
<P>
"Our quarter-final win over Sweden really boosted our
confidence," said Chinese team leader Li Furong. "We beat the
French team by strength, not by luck."
</P>
<P>
China nipped former world champion Sweden 3-1 and booked a
final spot after beating South Korea in four games.
</P>
<P>
"We have become a target of the world since we swept all seven
titles at the home soil in 1993," Li said. "I feel relieved and
happy now."
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Liu used his wickedly deceptive serves and
merciless follow-up attacks to defeat Gatien 21-19, 21-14 in the
fourth game. Gatien also lost its first game to China's world
No. 1 Kong Linghui.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Kong, who had beaten Gatien twice in the world
championships and World Cup two years ago, triumphed 18-21, 21-16,
21-17.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Chila evened the scores for France as he beat Liu in
the second rubber.
</P>
<P>
The 17th-ranked Chila, who had lost to Liu in the World Cup
last year, controlled the game with clever returns to Liu's
deceptive serves and strong topspin forehands, winning the second
rubber 21-17, 15-21, 21-10.
</P>
<P>
Chinese veteran Wang Tao put China 2-1 up as he won the third
game against Frenchman Damien Eloi, 21-10, 31-29.
</P>
<P>
"I was really nervous in the second set," Wang said after the
match. "I have never played to a score of 31-29."
</P>
<P>
Eloi made a tenacious comeback in the second game, winning five
points in a row to level 20-all, and then extended Wang to 29-29.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchman played an air shot on Wang's tricky serve and
then returned into the net to concede the match point.
</P>
<P>
Early in the day, South Korea beat Germany 3-0 to win the third
place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
