<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guinea Worm Cases Drop Greatly in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) said here today the cases of guinea worm disease in
Nigeria were reduced from 653,620 in 1987 to 12,282 at the end of
last year.
</P>
<P>
This is the result of the implementation of the UNICEF-funded
National Guinea Worm Eradication Program (NIGEP) in the country,
according to Emmanuel Gemade, UNICEF program officer in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The number of endemic villages also reduced from 5,872 to
1,360 during the same period, he said.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF officer attributed the reduction to methodological
control process adopted by NIGEP.
</P>
<P>
According to Ben Nwobi, NIGEP Northeast facilitator, the
country now is at the stage of "case containment", having
approached complete eradication of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Case containment is the early detection of any case of the
guinea worm disease and adoption of timely intervention measures
to arrest it, thereby ensuring there is no further spread.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
