<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Students Agree to Return to Class </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Lectures at the University of
Zimbabwe (UZ) are set to resume on a full scale on Friday
following successful negotiations between students and the
institution's administrators.
</P>
<P>
UZ vice-chancellor Graham Hill today said while certain
lectures had been going on this week, all faculties would be
fully operational by Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Through negotiations and dialogue with the students, we have
finally agreed that the lectures should recommence," he said.
</P>
<P>
The country's largest institution of higher learning was this
week plunged into a crisis as students protested the delays in
processing outstanding allowances for some first year and
returning students.
</P>
<P>
Students boycotted lectures saying they could not cope with
the recently introduced policy whereby the government only
provided grants and loans to cover tuition, accommodation and
other essentials, excluding clothing, food and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
Riot police who had moved onto the campus had left this
afternoon. 
</P>
