<HEADLINE> Strong Pound Makes Rate Rises Unnecessary, Says NIESR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Interest Rates do not need to rise
after the election on May 1st, the National Institute of Economic
and Social Research (NIESR) claims in a report on UK economy,
published today.
</P>
<P>
The institute believes an incoming government should resist
Bank of England pressure for a rate rise and should focus its
energies on delivering a Budget designed to put the public
finances on to a sound fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
That would involve a firm commitment to existing spending
targets as well as higher taxes.
</P>
<P>
The NIESR says that the strong pound has reduced the dangers of
overheating in the economy, making higher interest rates
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
The institute argues that the 15 percent rise in sterling since
the autumn will slow the economy down this year, reducing the risk
of overheating.
</P>
<P>
It has cut its growth forecast for this year from 3.5 percent
to 2.6 percent and is forecasting another quiet performance next
year.
</P>
<P>
The NIESR also believes that the benefit of cheaper imports
will help reduce the underlying inflation rate to 2 percent later
this year and is forecasting the rate of well below the 2.5
percent target set by the Government for next year as well.
</P>
<P>
However, Martin Weale, the NIESR's director, describes the
existing position as "unhealthy" and estimates that the annual
borrowing requirement is 24 billion US dollars higher than it
should be at this stage of the cycle.
</P>
<P>
The institute calls for prompt action, claiming that "from a
political perspective there is no better time to tighten fiscal
policy than in the early part of a new parliament".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
