<HEADLINE> Budget for Liberian Polls Pruned Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The 9-million-U.S. dollars budget
for Liberia's elections scheduled for May 30 has been
"drastically pruned down to realistic and realisable cost,"
according to Nigeria's Foreign Affairs Minister Tom Ikimi.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last week's assessment visit to Liberia, Ikimi
said the initial estimate of two million dollars for personnel
cost has been cut down to 700,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Likewise, the initial projection of just over seven million
dollars based primarily on the estimates of the donor agencies
for technical support and material assistance has also been
drastically reduced to a figure that conforms with ECOWAS
expectation," he said, quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria
today.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi did not say how much the election would now cost.
</P>
<P>
Nearly two weeks ago, Liberia's newly-installed Independent
Electoral Commission sent a detailed estimate of 12 million U.S.
dollars to General Sani Abacha, Nigeria's head of state who is
also chairman of ECOWAS (Economic Community of West African
States) and the Committee of Nine on Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The commission emphasized that the country would not be able
to source the funds necessary for the elections.
</P>
<P>
Last Monday Abacha sent an ECOWAS delegation, led by Ikimi, to
Liberia to assess the preparations already made for the
elections.
</P>
<P>
While announcing the budget cut, Ikimi noted that some members
of the donor community had not lived up to their pledges and
expressed the hope that now that the budget have been reduced to
realistic level, they would deliver on their pledges.
</P>
<P>
On the call for a rescheduling of the date for the election,
partly due to lack of fund, Ikimi said only the ECOWAS heads of
state could take a decision on such a "crucial and fundamental
matter".
</P>
<P>
He appealed to all those who had joined ECOWAS to carry "this
mission through to stay the course with us and engage in nothing
that may threaten the process at this crucial and delicate
stage." 
</P>
</TEXT>
