<HEADLINE> Turkey Positive Toward Relations With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Tansu
Ciller said today that Turkish people are positive toward
relations with neighboring Greece.
</P>
<P>
Ciller, also deputy prime minister, made the remarks following
her 40-minute meeting with Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos, who is in Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey, to
participate in the three-day business conference of the Black Sea
Economic Cooperation (BSEC).
</P>
<P>
The Turkish foreign minister said that "within this framework,
we exchanged views on several issues to further improve relations
between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
"I am very happy that we had the facility to listen to each
other's views to broaden the relations between the two countries,"
said Ciller.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Pangalos expressed his hope that the existing
problems between Greece and Turkey will be solved soon and more
positive relations will be set up, saying that cooperation and
positive ties will be for the benefits of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"We should do our best to overcome the problems of the past",
said Pangalos.
</P>
<P>
On April 15, Turkish Foreign Ministry Undersecretary Onur
Oymen and his Greek counterpart Yorgo Papandreu held "surprising"
talks for a solution to the problems between the two countries
during the European Union (EU)-Mediterranean Conference in
Valletta, Malta.
</P>
<P>
Later, EU current President and Dutch Foreign Minister Hans
Van Mierlo said that the meeting between Oymen and Papandreu is
important for the solution of the Turkish-Greek problems, adding
that such efforts will be continued in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece have long been at odds over a number of
issues including the limits of air space, mineral rights below
the Aegean Sea as well as the Cyprus problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
