<HEADLINE> Tajik Opposition Condemns Attack on President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The Tajik opposition "National
Revival" today resolutely condemned the terrorist act against
president of Tajikistan Emomali Rakhmonov, but ruled out the
political motivation of the act, declaring it as "a purely
criminal act".
</P>
<P>
According to the Itar-Tass news agency, opposition alliance
leader Abdumalik Abdulladjanov said in an exclusive telephone
interview with the news agency that his alliance and party "have
always been and will continue to be against resolving problems by
forcible means."
</P>
<P>
He stated that the opposition as a political party and a
political alliance have never had anything to do with criminals,
emphasizing that the opposition alliance would always struggle for
justice and for securing the solution to their problems
exclusively by political means, without any violence.
</P>
<P>
Describing the situation in Tajikistan as "extremely complex",
Abdulladjanov said the terrorist action in Khudjand might have
been caused by a complicated social and economic situation in the
republic.
</P>
<P>
He also did not rule out that the attack on the president was
relating to the recent events in the city Khudjand when 20 inmates
died in a clampdown on a riot in the local prison.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a similar view was expressed by deputy
leader of the allied Tajik opposition delegation to talks with the
government Abdunabi Sattorzodah.
</P>
<P>
Tajik President Emomali Rakhmonov was wounded this morning in
an attempt on his life, when a grenade hurled by a young man
exploded near him.
</P>
<P>
In the incident two people died and more than 60 were wounded,
including chairman of the Leninabad region Kasim Kasimov, his
deputy Akil Akilov, chairman of the Tajikistan's customs committee
Yakubdjon Saidov.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the attack was described as "an open political action"
by Rakhmonov's press secretary Zafar Saidov. 
</P>
</TEXT>
