<HEADLINE> King Hussein Allows Hamas Leader to Come to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's King Hussein has allowed
the would-be-deported Hamas leader Musa Abu Marzouk to come to
Jordan on grounds of humanitarian motives, it was disclosed here
today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the Jordanian News Agency, Jordanian
Minister of State for Information Affairs Samir Mutawe said this
stance on the part of King Hussein emanated from Jordan's firm
support for the Palestinian people and its efforts to remove
obstacles facing the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The United States will release Abu Marzouk soon and he will
then proceed to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Abu Marzouk, 46, was apprehended by New York immigration
officials in 1995 after a trip to the Middle East on grounds he
violated immigration laws by not declaring affiliation with
Hamas. He obtained a U.S. residency permit in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been involved in efforts to help secure the release
of the Hamas leader who is facing extradition from the United
States to Israel.
</P>
<P>
There has been reports that the Hamas leader could be sent to
Jordan instead of Israel as a compromise to avert possible
Palestinian violence that could undermine the peace process.
</P>
