<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen meets President Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 30 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Wednesday met with China's Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen at the White House.
</P>
<P>
Qian Qichen first conveyed President Jiang Zemin's cordial
regards to Clinton and told the president that he had good talks
with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and other cabinet
members. Both sides in their talks agreed to work together to
further improve the Sino-U.S relations on a healthier, better
course, he said.
</P>
<P>
He told the president that the main purpose of his visit to
Washington is to make preparations for President Jiang Zemin's
state visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton said he is looking forward to President Jiang
Zemin's state visit, which will be followed by his state visit to
China. He said the mutual state visits are of great importance and
both China and the United States should from now make full
preparations and solve some specific problems in the Sino-U.S.
relations before there can be any positive results through
President Jiang Zemin's visit.
</P>
<P>
He said We will show to the world through President Jiang
Zemin's visit that the United States and China are committed to
making the 21st century a peaceful and prosperous one with
responsibility and determination.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the United States and China can improve their
cooperations in many areas, for instance, in the trade area, where
they may further expand their relations.
</P>
<P>
Qian Qichen agreed with the president and said China attaches
great importance to the relations between China and the United
States and hoped to establish long-term, stable relationship
between the two countries through joint efforts.
</P>
<P>
Qian Qichen also exchanged his views with Clinton on such
issues as China's entry into the World Trade Organization, the
Most Favored Nation status for China, peaceful utilization of
nuclear energy, non-proliferations and Taiwan, etc.. 
</P>
