<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Defenses Missile Deal With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today dismissed
U.S. criticism over its decision to purchase the Russian-made
anti-aircraft missile system S-300.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing today, Government
Spokesman Manolis Christofides said "we believe it is the
country's obligation and right to see to its defense because the
Turkish occupation force is illegally armed up to its teeth, with
American arms."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the U.S. President Bill Clinton's bi-monthly
report on Cyprus, the spokesman noted the Turkish forces, which
occupied the northern third of the island since 1974, have
brought a large number of heavy duty U.S.-made tanks.
</P>
<P>
In his report for last December-January period, Clinton
describes Cyprus' decision to purchase the S-300 as "doubly
regrettable," taking into consideration "the already excessive
levels of armaments in Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also expressed concern over "threats of a military
strike by Turkey," linking them with the missile deal.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said the Cypriot government appreciates the
U.S. position on the Turkish threats. "We respect this position,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Turkey strongly opposes the Cypriot government's decision last
January to buy the Russian-made missiles and has threatened to
destroy them if they are deployed on the island.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman agreed with the U.S. government that "the
Cyprus problem will be solved through a dialog and not war."
</P>
<P>
However, Christofides dismissed part of the Clinton report
which claimed U.S. has successfully urged the Cypriot government
to delay the purchase of the missiles for 16 months.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. diplomacy did not pressure us on the delivery date," the
spokesman said, noting that the purchase contract defines the
date when the S-300 will be delivered.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot Foreign Minister Yiannakis Cassoulides also told
reporters today that he sees no reason for carrying on with this
discussion on missiles, as all efforts should now be concentrated
on reaching a solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
"We can take unilateral decisions, when we believe the timing
is right, to help the climate" for a solution, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has call upon President
Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash to
have face-to-face negotiations to find a over-all solution to
the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops landed and seized 37
percent of the territory after an Athens-backed coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
