<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda, Italy Issue Joint Communique on African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and Italy issued here
today a joint communique on matters of mutual interest concerning
the Horn of Africa and the Great Lakes region in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The communique was signed by Italian Minister of State for
Foreign Affairs in charge of development cooperation Rino Serri
and Ugandan Minister of State for Foreign Affairs in charge of
international cooperation Martin Aliker.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, Italy commended the efforts made by Uganda
toward the revitalization of the Inter-Governmental Authority on
Development (IGAD).
</P>
<P>
On Sudan, the two countries stressed the need for an effective
dialogue between the government and the opposition forces on the
basis of the declaration of principles as agreed by IGAD member
states in 1994.
</P>
<P>
On Somalia, Uganda and Italy shared the view that the ongoing
reconciliation process has reached a crucial stage and therefore
called upon all Somali groups to participate in the national
reconciliation conference.
</P>
<P>
On Zaire, Uganda and Italy expressed the hope that the
political situation will develop toward a profound renewal of
that country whose territorial integrity should not be by any
means jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
On Burundi, the two countries expressed support for the
on-going initiatives aimed at national reconciliation, genuine
democracy and security for all.
</P>
<P>
The two sides underlined the opportunity to expedite the
on-going negotiations regarding the agreement on the promotion
and protection of investments.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to creating a bilateral technical committee
in charge of seeking ways to promote mutual private investments
in specific productive sectors.
</P>
<P>
Italy proposed to start negotiations in such fields as
infrastructure, energy and telecommunications, transformation of
agricultural and livestock products, environmental protection
particularly in Lake Victoria.
</P>
<P>
Serri left Uganda today after his four-day official visit to
the eastern African country. enditem

