<HEADLINE> Akashi to Visit Iraq to Observe Oil-for-food Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 30 (Xinhua) -- U.N.
Under-Secretary-General Yasushi Akashi will visit Iraq on Saturday
to see how the oil-for-food deal is implemented in that country.
</P>
<P>
The deal allows Iraq to sell in six months up to 2 billion U.S.
dollars worth of oil to buy food and medicine, as an exception to
the sanctions imposed on Baghdad by the U.N. after its 1990
invasion of Kuwait..
</P>
<P>
A U.N. spokesman, in announcing the visit, said Akashi will
meet Iraqi officials, U.N. personnel and try to obtain first hand
information on how the oil-for-food deal has been implemented.
</P>
<P>
The deal went into effect in December and would expire on 7
June. The U.N. Secretary-General has to report to the Security
Council before the expiration of the oil-for-food deal. 
</P>
