<HEADLINE> U.N. Workers Begin Rwandan Refugees Repatriation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The repatriation of
refugees in eastern Zaire began today with the help of United
Nations aid workers, a U.N. spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Fred Eckhard told reporters at a regular noon
briefing here that the first flight of refugees left Kisangani,
Zaire, for the Rwandan capital of Kigali this afternoon local time
with 186 children aboard.
</P>
<P>
The second plane with 50 refugees was scheduled to depart for
Kigali later today, the spokesman disclosed.
</P>
<P>
He said that a total of 600 refugees were expected to be
brought back to their homeland today.
</P>
<P>
There are reportedly 80,000 refugees in camps south of the
regional capital of Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
Zairian rebels, who have taken control of the eastern half of
Zaire, have given the United Nations 60-day deadline to get these
refugees im camps back home to Rwanda, according to reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who had blocked previous U.N. attempt to repatriate
the refugees, are now threatening to move the refugees themselves
if U.N. aid workers could not act fast enough. 
</P>
