<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruling Party Wins Yemen's Parliamentary Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Yemen's ruling People's Congress
Party has won a majority in the parliamentary elections, the
Supreme Elections Committee announced here today.
</P>
<P>
According to the announcement, among 247 constituencies which
have already been declared, the People's Congress Party led by
President Ali Abdullah Saleh so far has won 157 out of the 301
seats of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The ruling party's coalition partner the Islah Party won 43
seats and independent candidates and other small parties won 47
seats.
</P>
<P>
Candidates competing for the house stood at 2,311, of whom 754
are party nominees, and 1,557 independent ones. About 4.6 million
of the country's 16 million population were registered to vote.
</P>
<P>
Four parties boycotted the elections -- namely, the Yemen
Socialist Party, the Unionist Grouping Party, the League of
Yemenites and the Union of Popular Forces.
</P>
<P>
The elections, the first since a two-month civil war in 1994,
attract extensive Arab and world attention.
</P>
<P>
A total of 141 international observers supervised the
elections, including Arab observers and others from the European
Union, the United Nations and some other countries.
</P>
<P>
But the Islah Party said the ruling People's Congress party
violated the law by interfering in the counting, threatening that
it will withdraw form the election process. There were also
reports of bloody clashes during the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
