<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Russian Proposal on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Government Spokesman
Manolis Christofides today expressed welcome to a Russian
proposal which he said could favorably contribute toward
efforts for a solution to the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The Russian proposal was put forward Tuesday during a meeting
of the U.N. Security Council permanent members in New York.
</P>
<P>
Describing the proposal as "positive," Christofides said at
his daily press briefing today that "since we are still at the
preparatory stage, it can be used along with other documents," at
any stage of the negotiations for a Cyprus solution.
</P>
<P>
He said the two High Level Agreements reached between the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides in 1977 and 1979, the
U.N. Security Council resolutions on Cyprus and a set of ideas
proposed by the U.N. in 1992, are among documents on the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the Russian proposal notes that
the solution to the Cyprus problem would ensure the
establishment of a bicommunal, bizonal federation, which will
safeguard the existence of one independent and territorially
integral state, with a single sovereignty, international status and
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
The proposal also rules out union of any part of Cyprus with
another country, as well as any form of division or secession.
It provides for the establishment of a demilitarized and
secular state.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the security of the future federal state,
which is one of the thorny issues in the Cyprus question, Russia
proposes it is safeguarded through international guarantees.
</P>
<P>
Christofides clarified that no decision was taken on the
Russian proposal by the five U.N. Security Council permanent
members, noting that a statement was issued after the meeting,
in which they outline how they see efforts to reach a solution
in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has proposed a face-to-face
direct negotiation between President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash to find a comprehensive solution to
the Cyprus problem by the middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a coup
by some Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
