<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-30 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Ministers Alert on Water Scarcity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Arab ministers of agriculture and
water resources today sounded warning of the scarcity of water in
the Arab region.
</P>
<P>
In the Cairo Declaration issued at the close of their two-day
conference, the ministers regard water as the region's "most
precious of natural resources" and the key for agricultural
programs and Arab food security.
</P>
<P>
The declaration spelled out the principles governing inter-Arab
cooperation in the use, development and protection of available
water resources in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We followed with deep concern external threats and policies
aimed at monopolizing and depleting water resources to which Arab
countries have legal share-rights," said the declaration.
</P>
<P>
The ministers asserted the importance of resolutions adopted by
the Arab League Council on protecting Arab rights to joint water
resources with neighboring countries outside the Arab region.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo Declaration praised national efforts to maximize
exploitation of available water resources through technical and
investment programs.
</P>
<P>
The declaration called for mobilizing Arab water rights at all
regional and world forums.
</P>
<P>
The conference was jointly organized by the Arab Organization
for Agricultural Development and the Egyptian Ministry of
Agriculture and Land Reclamation.
</P>
<P>
The conference is attended by Arab League Assistant Secretary
General Abdel Rahman al-Sihbani, Chairman of the Arab Organization
for Agricultural Development Yehia Bakour, Arab ministers of
agriculture and representatives from Arab and international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
A recent study has showed that the scarity of water and the
indifference to the issue has blocked the agricultural development
in the Arab world that lies in the desert belt over the equatorial
zone.
</P>
<P>
The study, the work of the General Secretariat of the Union of
Arab Chamber, cautioned against the negative impact of the limited
water resources on future plans for self-sufficiency in cereals.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of water in the Arab world is used in
agriculture and the rate goes even higher in countries like Egypt,
Iraq, Morocco, Oman, Saudi Arabia and Yemen.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has predicted that the per capita quota of fresh
water in the Mideast and North Africa per year will nosedive from
3,300 to 650 cubic meters over the period from 1960 to 2025.
</P>
<P>
By then, the Arab states will have to settle with two thirds of
the amount used by Asian countries or seven times less than the
international average, according to the bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
