<HEADLINE> Annan to Appoint Resident Special Representative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 30 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said today that he plans to appoint, as a successor to
his current special envoy for Georgia, a resident special
representative who will be based in Tbilisi and Sukhumi.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the Security Council, Annan said this is part of
the efforts in response to the increased demands arising from a
strengthened United Nations involvement in the peacekeeping
process.
</P>
<P>
He said he also intends to convene a meeting with both sides at
an appropriate location to map out the areas where concrete
political progress can be made. To strengthen the political
element of the 125-member U.N. peacekeeping force in Georgia, he
also intends to appoint a few additional officers specialized in
political, civil and legal affairs.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in Georgia, Annan said both parties to the
conflict seem determined to continue their direct contacts and to
broaden their bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to both sides to pursue, in this spirit, the
current discussions over the implementation of the decisions of 28
March 1997 adopted by the CIS (Commonwealth of Independent States)
Council of Heads of State.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, it was decided that states members should
endeavor to reach, as soon as possible, a comprehensive political
settlement of the conflict in Abkhazia, Georgia, and an agreement
on the return of refugees and displaced persons to their homes.
</P>
