<HEADLINE> Major Remain Optimistic on Eve of Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Despite the media prediction that
the Conservatives would lose the election with a crushing defeat,
Prime Minister John Major today remained optimistic and confident
that his party's economic achievements could guarantee victory.
</P>
<P>
"No one can honestly question that the transformation in
Britain has been anything less than an economic miracle. It's too
good to give up," he told the last news conference in the six-week
election campaign.
</P>
<P>
"It would be a tragedy if these opportunities were lost by the
false attraction of a well-packaged marketing scam," he added.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with BBC, Major said he still thought this
election was there to be won. "There are huge numbers of people
who are undecided," he said.
</P>
<P>
An NOP/Reuters opinion poll released 17 hours before voting
begins showed the Conservatives lagging 22 points behind Labor,
riding high on the support of 50 percent of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
But according to an opinion poll published by the Daily
Telegraph later today, the Labor Party's lead over the ruling
Conservatives has fallen seven points over the past 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
The Gallup poll released in the newspaper put Labor's lead at
46 points, down five points from a day earlier, while the
Conservatives' supports were up two points to 33.
</P>
<P>
Major said he did not believe the opinion polls, which wrongly
forecast he would lose the last election in 1992.
</P>
<P>
"I don't share their opinion... that we're going to lose
tomorrow. I think this election is there to be won. There are huge
numbers of people who are undecided," Major told BBC radio.
</P>
<P>
Most opinion polls conducted during the campaign period have
showed Labor leader Tony Blair enjoyed a comfortable lead of
around 20 percent over the Conservative party which has ruled
Britain for the past 18 years.
</P>
<P>
The 20-point lead showed by current polls would give Labor a
majority of around 200 seats, but the actual election outcome
would not be that size of victory and the majority could be around
100 seats.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Blair was also cautious about Thursday's result and
urged Britain's 44 million voters to come out and vote Labor to
avoid a fifth successive Conservative term.
</P>
<P>
"Let us together tomorrow come out, support the Labor Party,
build that better Britain and give our children the future they
need," he told voters in his last-day campaign tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
