<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Panel Moves on Tighter TV Ratings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- A United States Senate panel is
moving forward on legislation that would either force more
detailed television ratings, or forbid the airing of violent shows
when children are likely to be watching.
</P>
<P>
The Senate Commerce Committee today is expected to agree to
send the bill to the full Senate, which reportedly would consider
it as early as next month.
</P>
<P>
The bill came four months after the TV industry began rating
programs. It would require broadcasters and most cable channels
to either provide more detailed information about shows' violent
content, or air those shows only when children are not likely to
be viewing.
</P>
<P>
An identical bill has been offered in the House, but hasn't
been acted upon. A House panel will hold a TV ratings hearing in
Peoria, Illinois, on May 19.
</P>
<P>
The action turns up the pressure on the TV industry to
voluntarily strengthen its six-tier, age-based ratings system,
which went into effect on January 1.
</P>
<P>
Existing ratings use designations ranging from "TV-G", programs
suitable for all ages, to "TV-MA", for mature audiences only.
Most shows have been rated "TV-PG", parental supervision suggested.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Communications Commission would determine during
what hours violent programs would be banned. It is unclear which
programs would qualify as violent.
</P>
<P>
Members of the TV industry, meanwhile, have been meeting to
consider possible changes, but no decisions have been made.
</P>
<P>
Motion Picture Association of America President Jack Valenti,
who oversaw the creation of the industry ratings, said no major
changes would be made unless parents wanted them. The industry
would begin polling parents in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
