<HEADLINE> Germany Assures Romania of Entry into NATO, EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 1 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel today assured Romanian authorities of Romania's admission
to NATO and the European Union (EU), but he stopped short of
pledging support for its bid to join among the first new members.
</P>
<P>
Meeting Romanian President Emil Constantinescu, Kinkel said
Germany is keen to build a partnership with Romania in political,
economic, and cultural fields. Germany fully supported Romania's
integration into Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, Kinkel, who was on a two-day visit here, refrained
from promising that Romania would be one of the first invited to
join NATO. The Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland are so far
considered as most likely to be first.
</P>
<P>
He told Romanian Prime Minister Victor Ciorbea that it was
risky to make a promise to any applicant country.
</P>
<P>
The decision would be made at the alliance's summit in Madrid,
Spain, in July, he said, and any new recruitment would go ahead
only with endorsement from all its 16 members.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to give a promise, as any promise would be in
vain," Kinkel, who is also German Vice Federal Chancellor, told a
news conference later.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Kinkel met his Romanian counterpart, Adrian Severin.
They discussed developing bilateral links and dialogue on
international issues. A new German consulate will be set up in
the western Romanian city of Timisoara in May.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel was accompanied by more than 200 entrepreneurs, who met
economic officials.
</P>
<P>
Germany is the biggest trade partner of Romania, a partner in a
fifth of Romania's trade volume since 1990. It is also the second
largest investor of the Eastern European country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
