<HEADLINE> HK Returnee Rate Remains High in 1996: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's returnee rate, the
number of returnees recruited against that of staff who emigrated,
 remained high at 54 percent in 1996, a survey showed today.
</P>
<P>
The rate had peaked in 1995 at 60 percent, more than doubled
that recorded in 1994, according to a report published by the Hong
Kong Institute of Human Resource Management (IHRM).
</P>
<P>
The returning staff were mostly at managerial, supervisory and
professional levels and aged between 30 and 39, which was
consistent with the findings of IHRM's previous surveys.
</P>
<P>
They usually backed home from Canada, Australia and the United
States, the most popular destinations for Hong Kong emigrants.
</P>
<P>
The results also revealed that in 1996 about 0.82 percent of
the workforce left Hong Kong, slightly higher than the 0.76
percent recorded in 1995. Both figures were sharply lower than
those registered in early 1990's when there was a big outflow of
talents.
</P>
<P>
The institute surveyed over 180 companies covering all the
sectors of Hong Kong on a random basis before working out their
report.
</P>
<P>
Founded 20 years ago and ranking as a major human resources
management professional bodies in Hong Kong, the IHRM has
conducted annual surveys on emigrants, returnees and expatriates
since 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hongkong Bank Expands Insurance Business in Asia-Pacific Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking
 Corporation (HSBC) is trying to expand its insurance capabilities
 in the Asia-Pacific region by entering into alliance with one of
the world's insurance giant.
</P>
<P>
The leading bank in Hong Kong and Royal &AMP; SunAlliance have
signed an agreement which enables the bank to provide non-life
insurance products to its customers.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, HSBC Insurance, a subsidiary of HSBC, is
able to sell insurance products in areas where it is not licensed
to operate at present. HSBC Insurance will co-operate in marketing
and sale of some insurance products of Royal &AMP; SunAlliance.
</P>
<P>
The agreement excludes Hong Kong and Singapore, where HSBC is
able to offer its own insurance products.
</P>
<P>
David Elton, chief executive officer of the Hong Kong bank
regarded the latest development as an evidence of HSBC's
commitment to providing a full range of financial services in the
region. "Royal &AMP; SunAlliance offers the best overall regional
presence to complement the existing service provided by HSBC
Insurance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Royal &AMP; SunAlliance is one of the largest general and life
insurance companies in the world. It has total assets of 55
billion sterling pounds in more than 120 countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
