<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xiamen SEZ Increases Size Nine-Fold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The Xiamen Special Economic Zone
(SEZ) in southeast China's Fujian Province rose nine-fold in size
by absorbing Tong'an County today.
</P>
<P>
The county is now a district of Xiamen City. It covers a total
area of 1,079 sq km and has a population of 540,000. It used to be
the largest county in Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
This has enabled the 131-sq-km city of Xiamen to increase its
size by some nine times.
</P>
<P>
The county is the ancestral home to overseas Chinese living in
25 foreign countries and regions. It has attracted about 1.3
billion US dollars in overseas investment over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Last year the county, one of China's key production areas of
longan and vegetables, recorded a total industrial output value of
about 5.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The county is also noted for its production of peanuts, prawns
and lean-meat pigs for export.
</P>
<P>
Local observers say that the integration of Tong'an County with
Xiamen will greatly fuel the development of the overpopulated SEZ
and provide more rooms for its industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
