<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Trio Stands Fair Chance of St. Bride Vase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Wang Tao, Liu Guoliang
and Kong Linghui, the trio who won China's 12th Swaythling Cup for
the men's team event on Wednesday, stands a fair chance in the
men's singles contention at the World Table Tennis Championships.
</P>
<P>
"All three have a chance to win the St. Bride Vase for the
singles top honor," said Chinese head coach Cai Zhenhua, who has
outmaneuvered his Swedish and South Korean counterparts with
smarter lineups in the quarter- and semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Wang, the oldest member of the Chinese team,
has showed that he is more than a doubles expert with impressive
singles play for a decade.
</P>
<P>
The stocky lefthander, who won the deciding game against Jorgen
Persson in China's 3-2 victory over Sweden in the 1991
championship final and downed the Swede again in China's 3-1
quarter-final win on Monday, has never won world or Olympic
singles event.
</P>
<P>
"I really want to end my career with a singles championship,"
said Wang, who has won respect from top world players.
</P>
<P>
"Wang Tao is one of the greatest players and he has ability and
mentality to be a singles champion here," said South Korean ace
Kim Taek Soo.
</P>
<P>
Olympic double gold medalist Liu, who has kept a clean book
against Sweden's table tennis great Jan-Ove Waldner, is also a
title hopeful.
</P>
<P>
"Liu plays a lightning-fast game in penhold grip, the style
that Europeans don't get used to," said the Chinese coach.
</P>
<P>
"Liu is the most favored for the singles championship," said
Waldner, the only male who has won a Grand Slam of the Olympic,
world championship and World Cup titles.
</P>
<P>
Liu Guoliang, whose name means "pillar of the country" in
Chinese, is hailed as a reviver of the penhold style, which was
predicted to end up in a Darwinian-style extinction as more
players were turning to handshake grip.
</P>
<P>
Playing a modified penhold style, Liu sticks rubbers on both
sides of the racket and plays topspins with backhand. Tricky
serves and excellent footwork are his major assets.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Kong Linghui is the other Chinese favorite
in the singles event if history and form don't turn against him.
</P>
<P>
The men's singles game has been so closely contested that no
one has succeeded in defending his title since Chinese Jiang
Jialiang won the championship in 1985 and 1987.
</P>
<P>
Sweden's Jan-Ove Waldner lifted the singles title in 1989 and
conceded it to teammate Jorgen Persson in 1991. Gatien took the
1993 event but fell under a giant-killing spree by Kong in the
1995 Worlds.
</P>
<P>
"I will try my best to regain the title," said the 21-year-old
Kong, who outlasted former world champion Jean-Philippe Gatien in
China's 3-1 final victory over France on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Those able to break the Chinese stronghold are Waldner,
Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus, Gatien and Jean-Michael Saive of
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Waldner, the greatest table tennis improviser the world has
ever seen, reached his top form as he grabbed the only point in
the quarter-final, beating world No. 1 Kong for the fifth straight
time.
</P>
<P>
Fourth-ranked Samsonov, the most improved player in the world
since the 1995 championships, plays a consistent game without
obvious loopholes. The 21-year-old Belarussian made himself as
title-hopeful as he just conceded 13 points in a straight-set
routing of Waldner in a men's team group match.
</P>
<P>
Gatien and Saive, the most aggressive players in the world who
played in the 1993 championship and 1994 World Cup finals, remain
the threats to the best. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
