<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Discuss Membership Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of the seven
ASEAN countries are scheduled to meet in Kuala Lumpur later this
month to discuss the entry of Laos, Cambodia and Myanmar into the
regional grouping, a senior Indonesian official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the fact that the ASEAN leaders have agreed to accept
the three countries, they have yet to determine the appropriate
time for them to join the group," Foreign Minister Ali Alatas
said.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the ASEAN foreign ministers need to meet to reach an
agreement on when Laos, Cambodia and Myanmar could join the
grouping, he added.
</P>
<P>
Results of the meeting could be in the form of a recommendation
to be submitted to the ASEAN leaders during their next summit, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Alatas reiterated the ASEAN stance to accept the three
countries as new members without any pressure from advanced
countries.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever the results of the Kuala Lumpur meeting, they will
not be influenced by any pressure from advanced nations," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
He said there are other topics that will be taken up during the
Kuala Lumpur meeting but the entry of the three nations will be
given priority.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the membership of the three nations will not be
based on domestic developments in those countries, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
