<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Memo Signed to Regulate Internet Domain Name Registration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Some 150 delegates from all over the
world signed a memorandum of understanding here today to regulate
registration of generic Internet Top Level Domain names (gTLDs)
after a three-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
The self-regulatory framework under the memorandum consists of
the Depository of the gTLD memorandum, a gTLD Policy Advisory
Body, a gTLD Policy Oversight Committee, a Council of Registrars
and Administrative Domain Name Challenge Panels.
</P>
<P>
For the time being, the memorandum will cover only seven
newly-created gTLDs: .firm, .store, .web, .arts, .rec, .info
and .nom, and their registrars.
</P>
<P>
Before the expiration of an agreement giving the United
States-based Network Solutions Inc monopoly on registration
of .com, .org, and .net, the three existing domains and its
registrars will not be subject to the memorandum.
</P>
<P>
Under pressure, the National Science Foundation, a U.S.
government entity, has announced that it will not renew the
agreement when it expires in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
The memo will not cover the two-character TLD name space within
the Domain Name System, which is reserved for ISO 3166 country
codes from .af for Afghanistan to .zw for Zimbabwe, and some other
special TLDs.
</P>
<P>
Delegates to the Geneva meeting have arrived at no agreement on
the issue of selecting 28 registrars among seven regions in the
world by lottery as recommended by the Internation Ad Hoc
Committee to the session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
