<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK, Beijing Strengthen Telecommunications Link </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 1 (Xinhua) -- A new telecommunications service
launched today will provide an efficient way to transfer
large-volume data in high speed between Hong Kong and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Telecom, the leading player in Hong Kong's
telecommunications market joined hands with the Beijing
Telecommunications Administration (BTA) to launch the new service
called frame relay from May 1.
</P>
<P>
Frame relay is a packet-switching technology which allows
simultaneous communications with multiple end-points through a
single access.
</P>
<P>
Customers who want to transfer piles of files, send electronic
mails and transmit video image can take advantage of the service,
according to Joseph Ma, who oversees the international market
business in Hong Kong Telecom.
</P>
<P>
Ma also said that his company is now negotiating with
telecommunications authorities in other major cities in China and
other parts of Asia to extend the frame relay network.
</P>
<P>
Operating 3.6 million lines, BTA is a dominant provider of
telecommunications services in the Chinese capital city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanxi to Expand Environmental Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 1 (Xinhua) -- North China's Shanxi Province
will continue to increase its investment in environmental
protection this year, according to the "China Environmental News".
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the province spent some 735 million yuan
(about 92 million US dollars) on environmental-protection projects
last year, or 0.7 percent of the province's gross domestic
product. The figure was the highest in Shanxi's history.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years Shanxi has given priority to industrial
pollution control and urban environmental management. The
provincial government has earmarked 30 million yuan annually from
its revenue to help its major cities control pollution since 1984.
</P>
<P>
The province launched 259 environmental projects with a total
input of 735 million yuan in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
