<HEADLINE> Prisoners Released by Break Away Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The president of the break away
Republic of Somaliland, Mr Mohamed Haji Ibrahim Egal, has released
248 prisoners yesterday in a presidential decree.
</P>
<P>
According to the decree, the prisoners benefitting from the
presidential amnesty are those who did not commit armed robbery
and crimes related to homicidal acts.
</P>
<P>
The report also said other more prisoners are also being
pardoned with their period of sentences shortened, especially
those who committed easy crimes such as pickpockets and public
disobedience. According to the decree the amnesty came with due
respect for the Holy Eid Al-Ad-ha and the peace atmosphere now
being enjoyed by the people of Somaliland in general.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the capital of the break away republic, Hargeisa,
said the release of the prisoners followed an internal agreement
between elders from the former opposition clansmen and the
self-styl ed president himself over the matter. According to the
report, most of the prisoners are those captured by the forces of
Mr Egal during the fighting between him and the rebel forces
dominated by the Garhajis clan of Issak.
</P>
<P>
The release of the prisoners was highly welcomed by the
residents of Hargeisa who considered the move as a sign forward
to the strengthening of reconciliation of the Issak clansmen in
general. Among those who appreciated the release is the Sultan of
the Garhajis, Sultan Mohamed Rashid who returned back to Hargeisa
after a long absence with the rivals opposing Mr Egal.
</P>
<P>
The president of the break away republic, Mr Egal is expected
to announce soon his new government following his renomination
for the presidency of the republic during an election by clan
delegates in March this year. Mr Egal has been recently holding
an extensive consultations with the traditional and clan social
leaders over the formation of a representative government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there has been sporadic shelling between the forces
of Hussein Mohamed Aidid and those of Osman Hassan Ali Atto in
Bosnia vicinity and the strategic junction of k-7 this morning.
The shelling which has not been followed by ground attacks by any
of the warring sides has resulted in no fatalities, but the 120
mm rounds of mortars and anti-aircraft missiles have widely been
heard in south Mogadishu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
