<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Groups of Rare Birds Found on North China's Ordos Plateau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, May 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 5,000 relic gulls, a
species of rare bird, have been found living on the Ordos Plateau
in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The relic gull, with a dark head, red legs and white plumage,
is a type of bird on the verge of extinction, and is now under
first-class state protection in China.
</P>
<P>
Merely about 3,000 mature pairs survive in the world, mainly in
China, Russia and Mongolia, and some 40 percent of them live on
lakes in the Ordos desert region.
</P>
<P>
There was no record of the bird in China before 1987. But since
then Chinese experts have made seven investigation tours of the
Ordos Plateau and found at least three major breeding places of
the birds, with some 1,500 mature pairs on the plateau in 1993.
</P>
<P>
"To find such a large group of rare birds is really encouraging
when so many species are in an alarmingly dangerous situation,"
said an expert from an international bird organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
