<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moi: Kenya to Protect Local Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
today assured Kenyans that his government would protect local
industries from unfair competition from imports.
</P>
<P>
The president told a mass rally in commemoration of the
International Labour Day that a liberalized market should not
lead to unchecked import of goods.
</P>
<P>
Moi noted that the unchecked import of goods was to kill local
industries as some imported goods were subsidized and dumped in
Kenya's market.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Kenya's sugar and textile industries were
most seriously affected, leading to thousands of tons of sugar
unsold and dozens of textile factories closed following its
economy liberalized.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has undertaken economic reform programs for several
years in order to stimulate its economy into faster growth.
</P>
<P>
However, some of the measures taken during the reforms brought
difficulties to the low income category, rural population and
vulnerable groups such as women and the youth.
</P>
<P>
Moi pointed out that "we have gone past the worst part of this
process", adding that Kenya would continue its reform process as
the economic reform programs are "far from complete."
</P>
<P>
He said that his government was negotiating with donor
agencies to find a workable formula for further reform of the
economy.
</P>
<P>
In his address, the Kenya leader urged Kenyan people to
exploit the East African Co-operation and Common Market for East
and Southern Africa which, he said, the Kenyan government "has
spent much time and energy to build".
</P>
<P>
He noted that "time has come for Kenya to export its skilled
manpower" through the two regional bodies which can be used for
job creation and business opportunities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
