<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irish Beef not Banned in UAE But Difficult to Sell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The ban on the import of Irish
beef has been lifted in the United Arab Emirates (UAE), but
Ireland is still facing difficulties to share the local market, an
Irish official has said.
</P>
<P>
"The ban has been lifted only on paper but not from the minds
of the people", B.C George, general manager of Ireland's Farm
Fresh LLC in Dubai, one of the seven emirates of the UAE, was
quoted as saying by the local daily Khaleej Times today.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks a week before the arrival of the first
consignment of Irish beef to Dubai after the UAE officially
revoked the ban on April 12.
</P>
<P>
The ban was imposed by the UAE government since the scare of
the Bovine Spongform Encephalities (BSE), or mad cow disease,
surfaced in Europe, particularly in Britain and Ireland in April
1996. The disease reportedly could be transmitted to human beings.
</P>
<P>
Though the ban has been lifted, it is not easy for Irish beef
to re-establish itself in the UAE market, George said.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that currently there is a decline in the UAE
market for Irish beef because of fears on mad cow disease among
people and competition from Australian meat, which has become
very popular with UAE customers in the absence of Irish beef.
</P>
<P>
Many supermarkets in Dubai have shown no inclination to stock
Irish beef for the moment, since they stock Australian meat, as
well as meat from several other countries except European
countries, he proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
The Irish official said, however, he believed the decline is
just temporary and Irish beef could compete in the UAE market
with its "superior quality."
</P>
<P>
"The demand for Irish beef will spring back in the UAE once
people are convinced that Irish beef is free of mad cow
disease," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
