<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air France To Resume Paris-Shanghai Flight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Air France recently opened a
Shanghai office and announced that its direct flight from Paris to
Shanghai will resume next year.
</P>
<P>
Arthur Bullard, the airlines' regional general manager for the
Asia-Pacific, says that this reflects the increasing of number of
exchanges between the two countries and the city's importance as
China's commercial center.
</P>
<P>
Air France became the first European airline to enter the
Chinese market when it opened the Shanghai-Paris on March 30,
1947. Flights were halted in 1949, but service was restored in
1966, two years after the two countries resumed diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
Flights stopped once more in 1973, when the French carrier was
allowed to fly directly to Beijing. There are four Paris-Beijing
flights weekly. Passengers from Shanghai have had to go to Paris
via Beijing or Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-Paris flight takes ten hours. The new flight from
Paris to Shanghai will take 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
