<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Railway To Go To Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 1 (Xinhua) -- China's first railway, the
Songjiang-Shanghai line, which was laid by a British company in
1876, is being dismantled and all of the track and various
equipment will be put in a local museum.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after it began operation in 1876, the railway met with
a great deal of opposition because of fears of accidents, and the
Chinese government paid a large amount to purchase it from the
British owners and dismantled it.
</P>
<P>
The railway was rebuilt in 1896 and it extended from the
original 14.5 km to 16.1 km, entirely by the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The railway has played an important role in the development of
the local economy, but in recent years it has been criticized for
disturbing traffic because of its location in the downtown area
and the threat it poses to vehicles and pedestrians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
