<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kim Young-sam Under Fire Over 1992 Campaign Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The allegation that South Korean
President Kim Young-sam's ruling New Korea Party (NKP) spent much
more than the legal limit in the 1992 campaign is highlighted
after the first confirmation coming from an official of Kim's
party.
</P>
<P>
Kim Young-sam spent more than 150 million U.S. dollars for the
campaign, far exceeding the legal limit of 42 million dollars, Kim
Jae-dok, who worked as an accounting clerk in the NKP, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Though the NKP has claimed that it spent 32.6 million dollars
in the campaign, the opposition insisted that it told a lie and
demanded explanation on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Kim Dae-jung, an opposition party leader, alleged that
President Kim, then an opposition leader, received 2.3 million
dollars from then president Roh Tae-woo, who was sentenced
recently to 17 years in jail for mutiny, treason and taking bribe.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Hanbo group, which is under investigation for
a bribe-for-loan scandal, also provided huge amounts of money
during the 1992 campaign to President Kim.
</P>
<P>
The National Congress for New Politics (NCNP), another
opposition party, required Kim Young-sam, who took office in 1993,
to say whether Kim Dae-jung's allegation was true, while another
opposition leader Kim Jong-pil claimed that his United Liberal
Democrats (ULD) has evidence showing NKP's campaign spending
standing at 460 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
So far, NKP has dismissed as groundless the allegation. "Kim
Jae-dok was not in a position to know about the party's
expenditure during the campaign. We urge the opposition to stop
political maneuvering against us," its Secretary-General Park
Kwan-yong said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
