<HEADLINE> Iraq Lodges Protest Against US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today protested to the
U.N. against the U.S. violations of its territorial waters, the
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan, Iraqi
permanent U.N. representative Nizar Hamdoon said that on March
19, two U.S. frigates were engaged in maneuvers three miles to
the south of Iraqi al-Badr port in the Gulf waters, with a
U.S. helicopter hoved ring over Iraqi boats.
</P>
<P>
Another helicopter flew over Iraqi trawler "Diala" in the area
on the same day, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
It asked the U.N. chief to intervene in the issue and stop the
U.S. repeated provocations that "stand counter to U.N. charter and
rules of international laws and constitute a flagrant violation of
the sovereignty of a U.N. member state," according to INA.
</P>
<P>
It stressed Iraq's "inalienable right" to compensation for the
damage caused by such breaches in conformity with the principle of
international liability.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and the U.S. have been in a hostile state since August
1990 Iraqi invasion of Kuwait. In early 1991 the U.S.-led allied
forces defeated Iraq and drove the Iraqi army out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
About 20,000 U.S. forces are stationed in the Gulf area to
contain any aggression attempts of Iraq. Following the Gulf war,
the allied forces also set up two no-fly zones in the Kurdish
north and Shiite south of Iraq depriving the central regime of
access to the areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
