<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Hits 57-Month High in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar hit a record same-day
jump, reaching as high as 127.47 yen today in Tokyo, its highest
level since August 1992. It was triggered by stop-loss buying.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was changing hands at 127.37-39 yen at 5 p.m., up
from 127.13-15 yen at 9 a.m. and from 127.05-15 late Wednesday in
New York.
</P>
<P>
On the stock market, the key Nikkei index advanced moderately
as large-capital stocks such as Nippon Telegraph and Telephone
(NNT) lifted sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei index briefly topped a closing high for the year of
19,446.00 registered January 6, although late profit-taking erased
early substantial gains.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange ended at 19,275.33, up 124.21
points or 0.65 percent, from Wednesday's close.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all issues on the
First Section, gained 12.05 points or 0.84 percent to 1,453.24.
</P>
<P>
The volume on the First Section increased to about 600 million
shares from the previous day's 458.80 million shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
