<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Lower After Wages Data Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- A combination of stronger than
anticipated wages data and profit-taking caused the Australian
share market to fade to a marginally lower close today.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 2.6 points weaker at 2485.4,
after reaching a high of 2492.5.
</P>
<P>
"Most people thought the market would close five or ten points
higher, but there was nothing terribly brilliant. Today's trade
was not as positive as had been expected," brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics said today that in the
March quarter, the average weekly ordinary time earnings grew 1.3
percent, lifting annual wage growth to 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The is above the Reserve Bank's speed-limit level of 4.5
percent beyond which it believes wages growth becomes
inflationary.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed 4.4 points down at 1390.8, while
the industrials index dipped 0.7 of a point to close at 3905.6.
</P>
<P>
The bank index closed 9.2 points firmer, led by seven cents
rise from Commonwealth Bank.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was down 8.5 points to 1552.2.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 350.51 million shares, worth 758.25
million Australian dollars (591.4 million U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
