<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Proposes Greater U.N. Role Against Transnational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- China today called on the United
Nations to play a greater role in the fight against organized
transnational crime.
</P>
<P>
At the Sixth Session of the Commission on Crime Prevention and
Criminal Justice here, Zhang Geng, Deputy Minister of Justice and
head of the Chinese Delegation, said the U.N., as the largest
international organization, should become an information exchange
center and provide member states with prompt information services
and establish mechanisms to coordinate extradition and other legal
matters among member states.
</P>
<P>
He said an international instrument such as a convention
against organized crime should be elaborated in light of the
expansion and increasing damage of organized transnational crime.
</P>
<P>
Zhang called on the international community to provide
technical assistance to developing countries, which have the
majority of the world's population, relatively backward economy
and technology and are faced with more serious actual and
potential threats by organized transnational crime.
</P>
<P>
Zhang also said all states should strengthen cooperation in
accordance with the principle of equality and mutual benefit and
principles of international law, instead of the consideration of
ideology and values, so that criminals will not be able to find
any safe haven. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
