<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Polytech University Emphasizes Language Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Polytechnic
University is introducing a series of changes in all its full-time
programs including compulsory subjects in English, Putonghua
(Mandarin), written Chinese and general education.
</P>
<P>
According to the university, the next intake of full-time
students must pass the mandatory language subjects before they
will be awarded their qualifications. In certain programs, the
language grades may contribute to the classification of the final
award.
</P>
<P>
The schedule of the university shows that the mandatory
provision of English will be introduced in 1997-98 while that for
Putonghua and written Chinese will start in the following year.
However, some departments have elected to make the Chinese
subjects mandatory in their curricula in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
Poon Chung-kwong, president of the university, said that these
changes will be introduced because it is important for the
university to produce the preferred graduates who are competent
not only in professional skills, but also in their languages and
communications skills.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that English would remain the normal medium of
formal instruction as the institution will continue to promote a
bilingual culture and ethos.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the university has set aside 8 million HK dollars
(1.03 million U.S. dollars) for the establishment of an
independent General Education Center. The core staff of this
center will offer a variety of subjects grouped under five major
headings: scientific, historical, philosophical, aesthetic and
value judgments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
