<HEADLINE> Nigerian Civil Servants May Get Wage Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government may soon
approve a wage hike for civil servants and a review of their
working conditions, local paper the Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Head of State General Sani Abacha made the remarks on
Wednesday while receiving a report of committee for restructuring
the federal ministries.
</P>
<P>
"We strongly urge an urgent improvement in the conditions of
service to enable them to discharge their duties loyally and with
a sense of personal fulfillment," Chairman of the committee,
Allison Ayida told General Abacha.
</P>
<P>
In responding, General Abacha said the government will
carefully study the recommendation and state its position without
delay.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of several labor unions in the country have lamented
the biting economic situation in the Africa's most populous
country.
</P>
<P>
Raji Lawal, president of the National Union of Postal and
Telecommunications Employees said: "There is no cause for
Nigerian workers to celebrate the May Day in style, due to the
biting economic conditions ravishing workers."
</P>
<P>
General Secretary of the Nigeria Union of Teachers, Gabriel
Falad, said the union has no plans to celebrate the May Day as
ill-paid teachers are the worse hit by any economic imbalance in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
