<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Al-Assad, Mubarak Meet in Sharm el Sheikh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez Al-Assad and
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak held talks on ways to revive the
stalemated Mideast peace process in Sharm el Sheikh at the southern
tip of the Sinai peninsula today.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are expected to continue their frequent
consultations on the need to achieve a just, comprehensive and
durable peace in the region, the Egyptian MENA news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian president, accompanied by Egyptian Ambassador to
Syria Mahmoud Shokri, this morning arrived on a lightning visit to
the Egyptian Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh, about 500
kilometers southeast of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The meeting topped Mubarak's renewed diplomatic offensive to
revive the stalled peace effort by visiting Kuwait and Saudi
Arabia last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return from the two countries, Mubarak said he was
ready to organize a mini Arab summit grouping Jordan's King
Hussein, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Al-Assad but he made
this conditional on Israel's readiness to take steps to end the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak last week also offered to host a four-way summit
grouping Israel's prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, Arafat and
Hussein, on the condition that Israel halts settlement buildings
on Arab lands.
</P>
<P>
Syria has been advocating a comprehensive Arab summit to and
stronger reaction to confront the Israeli settlement practice, but
Egypt said such a move is still premature.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Syria began negotiations in 1991. But Israel broke
off the off-again, on-again talks last February after a spate of
suicide bomb attacks in Israel blamed on Palestinian extremists.
</P>
<P>
Syria insists it will not return to the negotiating table with
the Israeli government unless it first agrees to pull out of the
Golan Heights, captured by the Jewish state in 1967.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu rejects the demand, saying that the strategic plateau
is vital to Israel. But his predecessors, labor Party leaders
Yitzhak Rabin and Shimon Peres, reportedly verbally accepted an
Israeli withdrawal from the Golan in return for normalized ties
with Syria.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday Mubarak warned that Israel's hard-line policies
have catapulted the peace process to a "dark and dangerous
impasse."
</P>
<P>
Equally dangerous, he said, is the current stalemate on the
Syrian-Lebanese track "that is tempting the enemies of peace on
both sides to finish it off and drag the region to a dangerous
crossroads."
</P>
<P>
He insisted that a comprehensive settlement should be based on
the principle of land for peace.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian talks also broke down when Netanyahu shrugged
off international criticism on February 26 and approved
construction of the first 2,500 homes for Jews in the Har Homa
neighborhood of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want East Jerusalem to be their future capital
but Israel insists that Jerusalem remain undivided.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with the
Jewish state, has been a mediator in the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Seeks Peaceful Co-Existence With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has restated its foreign
policy of peaceful co-existence with neighboring countries,
calling for the establishment of a regional commission on the
settlement of boundary disputes.
</P>
<P>
The proposed Gulf of Guinea Commission shall comprise
Cameroun, Equatorial Guinea, Gabon, Sao Tome and Principe and
Nigeria, and be empowered to settle boundary disputes between
member states.
</P>
<P>
The call was made on Wednesday by Oladipo Diya, chief of
general staff, when he opened a meeting of the Joint Committee on
the Delimitation of Nigeria-Equatorial Guinea Maritime Boundary
in Abuja, the Nigerian capital.
</P>
<P>
According to Diya, such a commission should also be charged
with responsibility to demarcate maritime boundaries between
member states in addition to ensuring economic and agricultural
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We have a duty to prove to the international community that
Africans are determined to solve their own seemingly intractable
problems and conflicts," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot continue to depend on others for solutions to our
internal problems," Diya added.
</P>
<P>
Boundary disputes have hampered the development of relations
and economic cooperation between neighboring countries in the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and Cameroun have witnessed clashes in recent years
over the oil-rich Bakassi Peninsula in the Gulf of Guinea since
1992.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have pledged to reduce military tensions on the
border and improve relations. The dispute is till waiting for the
arbitration of the International Court of Justice at the Hague.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zaire's Mobutu, Kabila to Hold Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko
and rebel leader Laurent Kabila finally agreed today to begin
their first ever face-to-face talks at sea in a bid to seek a
peaceful solution to the country's spreading civil war.
</P>
<P>
Zairean officials said the meeting, initially planned for
Friday and to be mediated by South African President Nelson
Mandela, had been postponed till Saturday. The venue remains a
South African navy ship in international waters off Africa.
</P>
<P>
The encouraging step was welcomed by the United Nations
Security Council and other related countries currently mediating
the Zairean peace.
</P>
<P>
Kabila left his headquarters in southeastern Zaire earlier
today to visit some neighboring countries to prepare for the
coming South African-brokered talks.
</P>
<P>
Although the rebel leader claimed that the talks are aimed at
discussing how President Mobutu hand over his power gracefully,
there is no sign that the ailing president would step down.
</P>
<P>
A presidential spokesman said in capital Kinshasa that Mobutu,
currently troubled by cancer, had dropped plans to leave for
Gabon today en route for the talks.
</P>
<P>
"We understand the talks have been postponed until Saturday,"
Zairean Information Minister Kin-Kiey Mulumba announced.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, United States envoy Bill Richardson told reporters
in Kinshasa on Wednesday that there were no preconditions for the
talks.
</P>
<P>
At rebel headquarters in Lubumbashi, Zaire's second largest
city, a rebel spokesman said Kabila was surprised Richardson had
said "several African leaders" would attend the talks on the
supply ship Sas Outeniqua. The rebels do not want the talks to
turn into a mini-summit.
</P>
<P>
Richardson, U.S. Ambassador to the U.N., did not persuade
Kabila to accept a truce ahead of talks or a transitional
government before elections -- key components of a U.N. peace
plan devised by its special envoy, Mohamed Sahnoun, who will
attend the talks.
</P>
<P>
Kabila's rebels, who took up arms last October, have now been
in control of over half of the Zairean territory.
</P>
<P>
Latest reports said the rebels, on their march toward capital
Kinshasa, have now departed from their new forward base at
Kikwit, 400 km to Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
They also grabbed Bumba, south of Gbadolite, with no
resistance on Tuesday and were set to take Mobutu's nearby birth
place at Lisala. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
