<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Begin Casting Ballots in General Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain's 44 million voters today
began to cast their ballots in around 45,000 polling stations
nationwide in the long-awaited general election.
</P>
<P>
They will choose between John Major, the current Prime Minister
and leader of the ruling Conservative party, and Tony Blair,
leader of the major opposition Labor Party, to form a government
for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Security has been tightened in streets and around polling
stations for fear that the Ireland Republic Army (IRA), which
fights against British rule of Northern Ireland, might disrupt the
voting process.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few weeks, several explosions and bomb threats
have caused chaos and losses of millions of dollars in the country.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Major is seeking an unprecedented fifth
consecutive term, but has lagged behind the Labor leader Tony
Blair around 20 points during the six-week election campaign, the
longest in this century.
</P>
<P>
The last opinion polls released early Thursday morning still
put the Labor a lead between 10 to 22 points.
</P>
<P>
The Labor, meanwhile, is highly expected to oust the 18-year
rule of the Conservatives since Blair became the leader three
years ago and moved away from its socialist roots toward the
center of British politics.
</P>
<P>
Around 3,700 candidates have registered to run for 659 seats in
the House of Commons. The election results will come out on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the previous election in 1992, 77.8 percent of the
electorate of 43.2 million voted. The Conservatives won 336 seats
in the lower house and Labor 272. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 761 PKK Rebels Killed in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkish security forces killed 761
rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in the
military operations in southeastern Turkey in the first four
months of this year, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that 73 security personnel including village
guards also died in the armed clashes with the PKK during this period.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, 51 PKK members surrendered to the
Turkish security forces in the region over the past four months.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the government troops captured large
quantity of various kinds of weapons in the operations against
the PKK in the region.
</P>
<P>
The agency stressed that the government troops have been now
staging strong military operations in Tunceli of eastern Turkey
in a bid to wipe out the PKK guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
As there are better weather conditions in the mountainous
terrain in the region, the Turkish security forces are expected
to cross into northern Iraq to launch large-scale military
operations against the PKK rebels, who shelter themselves in the
area, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that about 150,000-strong Turkish troops are
stationed along the Turkish-Iraqi border lines to prevent the
PKK militants from infiltrating into Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a separatist war in southeastern
Turkey for autonomy since August 1984, in which more than 21,000
people, including PKK rebels, civilians and government troops
were killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
