<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Tightens Border Control to Curb Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
has worked out a border control strategy, under which most of
border posts would would close for commercial traffic within the
next three months, local daily the Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
The border control initiative represented a major step forward
in the fight against crime, Secretary of Safety and Security
Azhar Cachalia was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The number of land border posts through which bulk commercial
goods are imported or exported, would be reduced from 52 to 19.
</P>
<P>
The international airports authorized to clear international
flights would be reduced from 36 to 8.
</P>
<P>
Cross border flights which landed at unauthorized airports
would be seized, and the South African Air Force would be used to
track and intercept illegal flights, according to the plan.
</P>
<P>
Airfields to remain open include Lanseria, Johannesburg,
Durban Upington, Cape Town, Bloemfontein, Nelspruit and
Pietersburg. Meanwhile, all current sea border posts would remain
open for commercial traffic and normal border traffic would be
allowed at all border posts, Cachalia said.
</P>
<P>
The South African Department of Home Affairs, the Revenue
Service, the armed forces and police would join hands in the
border control campaign.
</P>
<P>
The new measures would be implemented at land ports within
three months and at airports within six months, Cachalia added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Include Russia in New European Security System: Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 30 (Xinhua) -- German Vice Chancellor and
Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel said that a new European security
system must include Russia and Russia's legitimate interests must
be given due consideration.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Romanian parliament today, Kinkel stressed that
the eastward expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) is not directed against Russia, which has been opposed to
the move, fearing it will threat its security.
</P>
<P>
On which countries will first be invited to join the alliance,
Kinkel said, NATO is still discussing the matter and no
predictions could be made.
</P>
<P>
He added that NATO will keep its door open to countries which
are not able to join immediately, but making no specific reference
to Romania.
</P>
<P>
The Rumania newspaper Adevarul reported today that Germany has
not agreed that Romania be admitted into NATO together with
Hungary, Poland and Czech at its Madrid summit in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
