<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 08:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Pursue "Look East" Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Iran is to pursue "Look East"
policies to expand its relations with Asian countries due to the
on-going diplomatic battle between Iran and European countries, an
Iranian top diplomat was quoted by the official news agency IRNA
today.
</P>
<P>
"Look East" policies will be brighter in the future and
Iran's ties with Asian countries will be expanded with greater
momentum, Iran's Deputy Foreign Minister Alaeddin Boroujerdi made
the remarks here Wednesday evening during a meeting with the
ambassadors of Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand, the Philippines and
Brunei.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed relations between Iran and the members of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and the
recent developments in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian deputy foreign minister for Asia-Oceania described
the future of relations with ASEAN countries as "even more
promising."
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi said that the recent developments proved this
principle more than ever before that the Asian countries are
important power base in the future world should the countries
strengthen ties and expand links with each other even more.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian government has to make a shift in its foreign
policy from "Look West" to "Look East" because there are too
much political pressure from the European countries.
</P>
<P>
The April 10 Berlin court verdict, accusing top Iranian leaders
behind the killing of four Kurdish opposition leaders at Mykonos
restaurant in Germany in 1992, sparked a crisis in relations
between Iran and Germany and other European countries.
</P>
<P>
Germany and Iran had recalled their ambassadors and expelled
four diplomats from each side. Ambassadors from the European
Union (EU) member nations, except Greece, had also been recalled
from Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Observers said that it would take a long time for Iran and the
EU member nations to amend their relations since the Iranian
government adopted a tough stance to the Declaration issued by the
EU in Luxembourg on April 29. Iran announced Wednesday that German
and Danish ambassadors were unwelcome back to Tehran.
</P>
<P>
At a ministerial meeting concluded in Luxembourg Tuesday, the
EU decided to suspend the "critical dialog" with Iran and to stop
the ministerial level contact between the two sides and continue
its arms embargo on Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0136 </DOCNO>
