<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Reinforces Foothold In South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Israel has redoubled its efforts
to strengthen its presence in the occupied "security zone"
in south Lebanon pending a political settlement, according to a
report of the pro-government Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
Brig.-Gen. Eli Amitai, commander of the Israeli Lebanon Corps,
said in an interview with the Air Force Magazine this week
that the air force had in the past three months used
advance weaponry in a number of missions against Hezbollah
guerillas in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He did not elaborate but said that the air force was
using new weapons that allow for much greater accuracy. "We
have hit the terrorists in places where they are still
gathering before setting out. The other side understands very
well the change and is being more careful now," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the London-based Jane's Defense Weekly as
saying that Israel has recently doubled the number of its
troops in south Lebanon to 2,000 men.
</P>
<P>
Amitai, who survived two direct Hezbollah attacks since taking
over command of the Israeli forces in Lebanon, said: "Today we
are attacking targets based on intelligence information and action
against infrastructure."
</P>
<P>
He admitted, however, that the Hezbollah group had also
acquired new weapons, saying that his forces found 17
shoulder-held Strella missiles hidden in a cave in the Litani
area. The missiles are capable of shooting down jets and
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
There have also been reports that Hezbollah fighters have
received new type of rockets capable of reaching the interior
area of Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
