<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 07:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Israeli-Turkish-US Military Exercises in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Israel and Turkey are working
to increase strategic ties, including holding joint military
exercises and combating terror, but both insist the strategic
alliance is not directed at any third party.
</P>
<P>
Today's Jerusalem Post reported that it was Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai's initiative to hold joint maneuvers
among Israel, Turkey and the United States who has already
agreed in principle.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai reportedly discussed the matter with his Turkish
counterpart Turhan Tayan, who is currently visiting Israel,
during their meeting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Tayan, arrived here Wednesday, will fly to the North today
for a first-hand look at the Lebanese and Syrian borders and
the Golan Heights, and to receive a briefing from Amiram
Levine, Northern Command of the Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
Tayan's visit is to set the stage for next week's meeting
with Turkish Deputy Chief of Staff Chabek Beer, who will be
leading the periodic strategic dialogue between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Israel is upgrading 54 F-4 fighters for the Turkish
air force in a deal worth over 600 million US dollars, and
both sides are discussing the possibility of another deal to
upgrade Turkey's F-5s in a deal worth over 300 million US
dollars, Israel Aircraft Industries officials said.
</P>
<P>
Israel is also competing with three other countries for a
deal to upgrade Turkey's M-60 tanks.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Tayan was received by a full military honor
guard at the Israeli Defense Ministry, after which he was
briefed on the threats facing Israel, particularly the
proliferation of surface-to-surface missiles and non-conventional
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai told Tayan that both Israel and Turkey suffer
from the threat of terror and that Israel is willing to
extend aid to Turkey in combating terror.
</P>
<P>
"The security cooperation between Israel and Turkey is not
directed against any third party," Mordechai said. "Cooperation
is vital for both countries and for strengthening the
stability of the Middle East."
</P>
<P>
Tayan said the strategic cooperation "is not pointing arrows
at any third party, and Turkey sees relations as very
important and I believe they will bring stability to the
region and advance the peace process." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Govt Disappointed with U.S. 301 Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government today
expressed its disappointment at the decision of the U.S. Trade
Representative to place Hong Kong on the "Watch List" in the
context of its Special 301 review on the protection of
intellectual property rights (IPR).
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Hong Kong government said, "Given the
considerable and persistent anti-piracy efforts and initiatives
the government has made, we consider it most unjustified to place
Hong Kong on the list."
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong has been taking vigorous enforcement
action at the retail, distribution and importation levels.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Customs conducted over 1,000 raids and seized nearly
one million copies of CDs, VCDs, and CD-Roms, which was 164
percent of those seized in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the estimated value of the seizure was
47 million HK dollars (6.06 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has established a very good liaison network with IPR
enforcement authorities on the Chinese mainland to stop copyright
products from entering Hong Kong, he said, adding that a number of
parallel operations have been mounted with Customs and relevant
Chinese authorities at the border.
</P>
<P>
He said that courts are also handing down much heavier
penalties for persons convicted of copyright piracy. In 1996, 144
persons received immediate custodial sentences for offenses
relating to copyright piracy, compared with 18 in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
