<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 07:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Settlement Expansion Activities Stepped Up In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Jewish settlers have constructed
new fences and roads as part of their on-going moves to expand
settlements in the occupied West Bank, the state-run Israel Radio
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Eli Suissa toured the northern West Bank
Wednesday expressing government support for the settlers'
activities and promising more help for them.
</P>
<P>
The settlers revealed that the Interior Ministry had pledged
to allocate additional funds for the expansion.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Palestinians charged that 4,000 donams (375.6
hectares) of Palestinian-owned land had been confiscated to
allow the expansion of the Efrat Settlement.
</P>
<P>
Even Harow, a spokeswoman for Efrat, said that in 1991, the
settlement received 5,000 donams (469.5 hectares) of state-owned
land from the government. She claimed that of the 5,000 donams,
only 1,000 donams (93.9 hectares) had been developed so far. In
addition, she said, approximately 500 donams (46.95 hectares) on
Har Hazayit are being developed.
</P>
<P>
Yehudit Tayar, an official of the Council of Jewish
Communities in Judea, Samaria and Gaza, called the Palestinian
accusations ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
"It is obvious that there is a land battle going on, and it
is no secret that the Palestinians have called for illegal
building in order to stop settlement expansion," she said.
</P>
<P>
Lt. Peter Lerner, a spokesman for the Israeli Civil
Administration in the occupied West Bank, said that the
administration advertised in the Palestinian press two weeks ago
outlining the current project in Efrat and stipulating that
objections should be registered within 45 days.
</P>
<P>
On a live satellite interview broadcast on CNN Wednesday
night, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu denied the
government had planned to construct new settlements.
</P>
<P>
"Any construction taking place is within the current municipal
boundaries," he said, arguing that Palestinians are also
building in their villages.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has all along maintained that the occupied
Palestinian territories are part of the State of Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
