<HEADLINE> Free Trade Among SAARC States to Start in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 1 (Xinhua) -- South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) is making hectic efforts to start
free trade among its seven member states by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
It is need of the hour that the mutual trade among the SAARC
countries be promoted for the well-being and economic prosperity
of the people in the region, said President of the SAARC Chamber
of Commerce and Industry (CCI) Salman F. Rahman of Bangladesh,
according to local newspaper reports today.
</P>
<P>
SAARC groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal,
Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
At the conclusion of a meeting between the CCI and the
Federation of Pakistan Chambers of Commerce and Industry, Salman
said Wednesday in Lahore, capital of Punjab province, that the
liberalization of trade and reforms are the order of the day in
the world. Therefore, SAARC countries should ignore the political
cooperation to promote regional trade.
</P>
<P>
He maintained that the private sector is being given top-most
importance in the world and the South Asian countries should also
bury the hatchet and boost mutual trade ties to bring about
economic revolution in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We have very limited time to enhance trade activities among
the SAARC countries as we have to strengthen each other by the
year 2005 so that in the free global trade, we could survive and
complete with the established economies of the world," Salman
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that SAARC countries constitute 25 percent of the world
population but the quantum of trade among themselves is merely
three percent of total trade which they carry out with other
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
