<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brisk Consumer Market in China in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The latest figures from the State
Statistics Bureau show that China's consumer market did well in
the first quarter of this year, with total retail sales hitting
663.3 billion yuan-worth.
</P>
<P>
The figure was up 12.6 percent from the same period of last
year in real terms, according to the Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, central China saw the quickest expansion of the
consumer market, as the retail volume of consumer products there
was up 18.3 percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the growth rate of retailed consumer products in the
eastern and western parts of China was just 15.2 percent and 13.9
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Official sources say that China has seen a favorable balance
between supply and demand of consumer products over the past three
months, with the prices of major agricultural and sideline
products remaining stable.
</P>
<P>
In the past three months China has purchased a total of 118.5
billion kg of grain, an increase of 25.5 percent on a year-on-year
basis, and 93 percent of the country's total output of light
industrial products was sold.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also indicate that China witnessed substantial
growth in sales of the following industrial products in the first
quarter of this year: wide-screen TVs, up 110 percent from the
same period of last year; personal computers, up 63.5 percent;
air-conditioners, up 47.2; and fax machines, up 160 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
