<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Hot Property Raises Fears of Thai-Style </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Despite precautionary measures taken
by the Philippine Central Bank, the country's stock market
continued to slide sharply Wednesday amid fears that a Thai-style
financial crisis could occur in the country.
</P>
<P>
Weak corporate earnings, coupled with wide-spread nervousness
over bank lending to the property sector, made Tuesday's stock
market in the Philippines fall 4.5 percent, or 128.87 points, to
2708.44, the lowest level in two years.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to allay fears of a property-related financial
crisis, the central bank Tuesday enforced the 20 percent cap on
bank lending to real estate firms and gave banks one year to do
so. However, the market fell further Wednesday by 60.27 points to
2648.17.
</P>
<P>
What has happened in the Philippines in the past few days shows
that foreign investors' confidence in the country has not been
restored since a property-related crisis took place in Thailand
recently, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
That is why foreign investors continued to shift their funds to
markets in other regions in spite of precautions taken recently by
the central bank, they said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past four years, financial and securities companies in
Thailand borrowed a large amount of U.S. dollars at low interest
rates and loaned up to 30 percent of their portfolios to the
property sector.
</P>
<P>
The moves resulted in over-supply of housing units. In Bangkok
last year, 600,000 square meters of office space came on the
market, of which more than half remains unleased. But another
900,000 square meters is planned for this year and 1.3 million
square meters for next year.
</P>
<P>
Compared with Thailand, the Philippines' picture looks better.
Central bank limits keep banks from putting more than 30 percent
of total loans in any one sector. The Philippine Central Bank
indicated in a study that property lending accounted for an
average of 11 percent of banks' loan portfolios in 1996.
</P>
<P>
But some economists said that banks' real exposure to the
property sector is much higher than the official data, perhaps
ranging from 15 percent to 24 percent of the total portfolios.
</P>
<P>
If a Thai-style crisis happens anywhere, analysts said, the
dubious honor could go to the Philippines, partly because of its
spectacular loans growth over the past several years and its high
U.S. dollar borrowing.
</P>
<P>
While total bank assets in the country have increased 25
percent annually on average between 1992 and 1996, bank loans
surged 42 percent in 1996 after jumping 43 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
To avoid the Thai-style crisis, the bank took steps to limit
bank exposures to the property sector. In the Philippines, where
property is used as collateral for a loans, banks now can not lend
more than 60 percent of the appraised value of that property. That
is the new banking rule in addition to the 20 percent limit
imposed on banks' real estate lending.
</P>
<P>
Economists hailed the precautions taken by the central bank,
saying that the news rules could cool down the over-heating of the
property sector in the future.
</P>
<P>
But they still doubt the measures could restore investors'
confidence in the country soon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
