<HEADLINE> U.N. Solar Scheme in Zimbabwe to Surpass Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 1 (Xinhua) -- About 7,000 solar lighting systems
have been installed in rural areas of Zimbabwe under the United
Nations Global Environment Project, now in its final year of the
pilot phase.
</P>
<P>
Launched in 1993, the five-year pilot program funded by the
U.N. Development Program (UNDP) and the Zimbabwe government, taps
the abundant solar energy through the installation of low-cost
photovoltaic systems, according to a UNDP spokesman today.
</P>
<P>
The initial target of 9,000 installations by the end of this
year is expected to be surpassed given the rate at which the
systems are being installed.
</P>
<P>
So far, installations have been made in households and
institutions such as clinics and schools. About 50 companies are
involved in the installation process resulting in the creation of
more than 500 jobs since the project was commissioned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
