<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Trafficking Urged to Be on South Asian Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Participants at a regional seminar
in this capital city of Nepal have urged South Asian governments
to take a serious and collective measure to control the rampant
women trafficking in the region.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, titled "Roundtable on Women Trafficking in South
Asia," was held here Wednesday by an organization called the Asian
Women Human Rights Council.
</P>
<P>
Reports made public at the seminar said that women trafficking
for prostitution has become a common problem of South Asian
nations.
</P>
<P>
Unofficial estimates showed that about 100,000 to 160,000
Nepali women are working in brothels in Mumbai and Calcutta of
India and 35 percent of them are abducted to India under false
promises of marriages and jobs.
</P>
<P>
India serves as the basic transit and stopover point for
trafficked South Asian women, the participants said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Bangladeshi girls are mostly trafficked to
Pakistan where there are over 200,000 Bangladeshi women, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Although Sri Lanka has no cross-border women trafficking
problem like that in other South Asian countries, the island
country is facing the increasing cases of trafficking women from
rural to urban areas, according to a Sri Lankan participant.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the seminar said that though trafficked women
are not necessarily forced into prostitution, they are mostly
commercially exploited and sold into slavery for domestic work,
illegal bonded labor and even the thriving human organ trade.
</P>
<P>
The governments in South Asia should look at the problem
seriously and discuss it at the regional level, they argued.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of the participants will lobby the heads of states
or governments at the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) Summit, to be held in Maldives from May 12 to
14, for putting the women trafficking issue on the agenda,
organizers said.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Maldives, Nepal,
Pakistan, and Sri Lanka.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Hikes Overnight Borrowing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
Wednesday hiked its overnight borrowing rates from 10.25 percent
to 11 percent to prevent the peso from depreciating.
</P>
<P>
The bank's overnight lending rate, on the other hand, was
retained at 12.65 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the market scrambled for dollars at the
Philippine Dealing System amid heavy selling of the local
currency, as foreign fund managers liquidated peso-denominated
assets in considerable volumes after the local stock market
continues to hit historic lows.
</P>
<P>
The peso thus dropped to a year low level of 26.375 pesos
against the dollar from the previous day's 26.369 against the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's increase in interest rates was intended to
make peso-denominated assets more attractive, since higher rates
similarly translate to higher yields. The hike was thus sanctioned
to quell speculative attacks against the local currency.
</P>
<P>
At Wednesday's trading, traders estimated that the central bank
had sold more than 100 million U.S. dollars to temper the local
currency's depreciation.
</P>
<P>
Total market volumes increased to 306 million dollars from the
previous day's 184.4 million dollars, traders said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank took the action after the local stock market
plunged further Wednesday to new two-year lows. The Philippine
Stock Exchange composite Index fell 60.27 points, or 2.23 percent
to 2648.17 at Wednesday's close amid fears that a property-related
crisis could take place in the country.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time since January last year that the index
sank to the 2600 level. It has lost 224.20 points, or 7.81 percent
in the past three trading days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
