<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopes Spain Lead in NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said today that he expected Spain to lead in the 16-member North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Speaking before meeting visiting Spanish Prime Minister Jose
Maria Aznar, Clinton said that "We want Spain integrated fully
into the NATO command structure," saying he expected Spain to
play "an important leadership role."
</P>
<P>
However, Clinton said, "Details of all that have to be worked
out by the command structure."
</P>
<P>
"We look to the Spanish to lead in NATO, to be willing to do
what has to be done to save situations which may not be
immediately popular, but which are profoundly important," Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
Though Javier Solana, NATO's secretary-general, is a Spanish,
the country has not fully joined the military structure of the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
"We're very fortunate in having a secretary-general of NATO
from Spain," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival Tuesday, citing Spain's decision last year
to fully join the alliance's command structure, Aznar said that he
wanted "clear recognition" of his country's growing role in the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
NATO is to convene its special summit in Madrid in July to
decide on expanding into the Central and Eastern European
countries.
</P>
<P>
"Having Madrid be the site of this historical summit when we
will vote for the first time to take in new members ... symbolizes
the importance of the role that Spain will play in the years ahead
in NATO," Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
