<HEADLINE> Thailand to Prevent Speculative Land-Grabbing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Thai Interior Minister Sanoh
Thienthong pledged tough measures to prevent speculative
land-buying or land-grabbing by foreigners after the government
relaxed rules on foreign ownership of land and housing.
</P>
<P>
He said on Wednesday that the relaxation of rules on foreign
ownership of land and housing would not be tantamount to "putting
the whole country up for sale."
</P>
<P>
He added that the country's new rules on ownership of land by
foreigners will meet international standards.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the cabinet, acting under pressure from the
property slump, agreed to seek parliamentary approval to amend
land and condominium laws to increase the right of foreigners to
own property.
</P>
<P>
The property market of Thailand is facing an oversupply, which
has lasted for about four years.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors will be allowed to own up to one rai of land
(0.16 hectares) for commercial use and 10 rai (1.6 hectares) for
industrial purposes.
</P>
<P>
A foreigner who has married a Thai spouse or has brought in
more than 1 million US dollars in capital will be allowed to own
one rai of residential land.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ownership in a condominium complex will be raised from
the current 40 percent limit to 100 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
