<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore to Import Natural Gas from Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Singapore will start importing
piped natural gas from Indonesia under an agreement concluded
Wednesday between a consortium of Singapore companies and
Indonesia state oil company Pertamina, the Straits Times reported
here today.
</P>
<P>
It said the consortium plans to import 325 million standard
cubic feet per day of natural gas for an initial 22 years, and
this is equivalent to about 300 million US dollars worth of
natural gas a year.
</P>
<P>
A giant 480-kilometer underwater pipeline will be built to
transport the gas with first delivery expected in the year 2000,
it said, adding that a final "gas sales agreement" is expected to
be signed later this year.
</P>
<P>
Led by Sembawang Engineering and Construction (Sembec), a
subsidiary of listed Sembawang Corporation, consortium members
include Tuas Power Pte Ltd (TP) and the EDB Investments, a
subsidiary of the government Economic Development Board (EDB).
</P>
<P>
It was understood that the Sembec and EDB Investments will
together hold a majority stake, while the respective stakes to be
taken by the members are still being worked out.
</P>
<P>
The Straits Times said the agreement is important as it opens
up Indonesia, with its substantial gas reserves, as an alternative
energy source for Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Singapore currently imports 150 million standard cubic feet of
natural gas per day from Malaysia to fuel its power stations under
a 15-year contract which expires in 2007.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
