<HEADLINE> Nepal to Introduce New Transport Policy Soon: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government is to adopt
a new transport policy soon after revamping the overall transport
system of the country, Transport Minister Bharat Mohan Adhikari
said today.
</P>
<P>
The Transport Ministry has formed a task force in order to
formulate the policy which will encourage the private sector's
role in the development of transport means, Minister Adhikari was
quoted as saying by official daily the Rising Nepal.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the task force has been directed to come up
with a concrete report within three months.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the paper, Adhikari said his ministry is
in the process to activate the governmental agencies related to
the transport sector, which have not been able to perform well in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
Stating that currently 20 of the country's all 75 districts
still have no link roads, the minister said his ministry is
expected to submit a proposal on road construction in these
districts to the next session of parliament.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will give top priority to the construction of
roads in rural areas with foreign assistance in line with the
government's long-term Agriculture Prospective Plan, he said.
</P>
<P>
An Asian Development Bank (ADB) study showed that Nepal needs
20,000 kilometers of rural roads to facilitate the transport of
agricultural products to different destinations in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
