<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy to Lift Ban on Its Royal Family </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Italian government today approved a
proposal put forward by Prime Minister Romano Prodi, which allows
the male heirs of Italy's former royal family to return to their
homeland, officials said today.
</P>
<P>
A measure to repeal Article 13 of the Italian constitution's
transitional norms laying down the ban on their return will be
approved at a government meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Italians voted down the monarchy, tainted by its links to
Fascism, and opted for a republic in a referendum in 1946. The new
republican constitution banning the House of Savoy's male heirs
from the Italian territory went into force on January 1, 1948.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Premier Walter Veltroni said the decision to speed up
the royal family's return was not a shift to the right in the
government's line: "Absolutely not, the government is above
suspicion on that."
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of the Communist Refoundation party, Marco Ferrando,
said the decision was made in the overall context of "historical
revisionism", a term usually taken to cover the rehabilitation of
Nazism and Fascism.
</P>
<P>
Others saw a more Machiavellian aim in the measure. "I've no
doubt at all, they want to win the election in Turin," said
Clemente Mastella of the Christian Democrat Center, part of the
opposition Freedom Front.
</P>
<P>
Turin, which is voting in the runoff mayoral race on May 11, is
the capital of the Italian part of Savoy and still feels strong
links with the royal house that once ruled it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, Laos Sign Accord on Second Bridge Across </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Laos signed Wednesday
an agreement to build a bridge across the Mekong river linking
Thailand's Mukdahan province and Laos' Svannakhet province,
according to a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The accord on the project was signed in Mukdahan, northeastern
Thailand, by Thai Transport and Communications Minister Suwat
Liptapallop and his Lao counterpart Phao Bounnaphonh.
</P>
<P>
Thailand and Laos will bear equal shares of the construction
cost of the 2 km bridge, estimated at 1.25-billion-baht (50
million US dollars), to be borrowed from Japan's Overseas Economic
Cooperation Fund, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The bridge, expected to be completed in 2000, will have two
lanes and space for two more, and a lane for a railway tracks. The
Asian Development Bank provided 3 million dollars for the design
work.
</P>
<P>
Along with the second bridge agreement, Thailand has promised
to build a 3.5 km road worth 103 million baht in Vientiane at no
charge. Construction is expected to be completed by December 2,
1998, when Laos celebrates its national day.
</P>
<P>
The first bridge across the Mekong river between Thailand and
Laos opened in 1993.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
