<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Witnesses Recall Birth of China's Regional Autonomy System (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, May 1 (Xinhua) -- "It is precisely because of this
system that China has successfully handled its ethnic issue," said
Bater. "I'm very proud that I was a witness to the system's birth."
</P>
<P>
Bater, 70, is a resident of Ulanhot, a city in the eastern part
of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region in north China.
</P>
<P>
On this day 50 years ago the regional government of Inner
Mongolia was founded there, and Bater, then a young Mongolian
herdsman, attended the founding ceremony.
</P>
<P>
That day signified the start of China's system of regional
autonomy for ethnic minorities. The system was later introduced to
Xinjiang, Ningxia, Guangxi and Tibet, where ethnic minorities
dominate the local population.
</P>
<P>
"When the establishment of the autonomous region was announced,
I shouted my approval," Bater recalled. "But my voice was drowned
by the deafening applause of the other people there."
</P>
<P>
Bater, who retired in the 1980s as the deputy director of the
standing committee of the municipal people's congress, the local
legislature, is now writing his memoirs, titled "An Unforgettable
Fifty Years."
</P>
<P>
"I must record everything I saw and heard of the system of
regional ethnic autonomy, to pass it on from generation to
generation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Before 1947, he said, Ulanhot only had 10,000-plus residents,
and had no industry or commerce. Life was extremely difficult for
the Mongolian people.
</P>
<P>
The city has now developed into a modernized industrial
community, with a prosperous economy, convenient communications
and a thriving population.
</P>
<P>
"Personally speaking, I turned from a penniless herdsman into a
government official in charge of ethnic affairs, thanks to the
ethnic policy of the Communist Party of China (CPC)," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Witnesses Recall Birth of China's Regional Autonomy System (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Han Tangshu, 86, was also one of the 393 people's delegates
attending the autonomous region's founding ceremony half a century
ago.
</P>
<P>
"At that time the Japanese invaders had just surrendered, and
there was a power vacuum in Ulanhot," he recalled.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the serious ethnic discrimination during the
reign of the Kuomintang and the Japanese, he said, people of all
ethnic groups were afraid that their rights could not be
guaranteed under the new government.
</P>
<P>
"Their worries were dispelled by the introduction of the
regional autonomy system, which affirmed the dominant role of the
Mongolian ethnic group in regional management, and also protected
the rights of the other ethnic groups," he noted.
</P>
<P>
In 1954 Han was elected deputy mayor of Ulanhot by the
municipal people's congress, and became the city's first deputy
mayor from the Han nationality, the country's largest ethnic group
but a local ethnic minority.
</P>
<P>
"On the basis of mutual respect and understanding, I cooperated
quite well with my colleagues from the Mongolian and other ethnic
groups," he said, adding that the city's rapid development during
the past few decades should be attributed to the realization of
ethnic equality.
</P>
<P>
Liu Shifan, who is of the Mongolian ethnic group, was only 16
when he attended the founding ceremony of the autonomous region,
but he still clearly remembers the remarks made by a living Buddha
named Aji at the ceremony:
</P>
<P>
"Aji said that the regional autonomy system would protect the
rights of all lamas and greatly benefit the development of
Buddhism all over the region," Liu recalled. "Now his words have
become true."
</P>
<P>
He said that both the central and regional governments have
fully guaranteed the people's freedom of worship, funded the
renovation and rebuilding of monasteries, and set up special
schools for training lamas.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are more than 100 monasteries in the
autonomous region, which accommodate some 3,700 lamas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
