<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 27 in Albanian Explosions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- At least 27 people were killed, 12
of them children, in explosions at an underground Albanian
military weapons store outside Tirana Wednesday, police said.
</P>
<P>
The figure has earlier been put at 22, but authorities said the
number of casualties is expected to rise further as many families
lived near the depot.
</P>
<P>
"All the people that were inside the store at the time were
killed," a government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear how the incident was triggered, but police said
that it was triggered as villagers were looting the weapons depot
for the brass casings of artillery shells for sales to make a
living.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Shakir Vukaj and some interior ministry
officials have rushed to the site for further investigation and
demanded measures be taken to avoid more blasts in the seven
depots nearby.
</P>
<P>
Eight people were killed last week when looters firebombed a
weapons store near Lezha, 55 kilometers north of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Since the outbreak of violence in Albania in January after the
collapse of bogus investment schemes, many army depots have been
reportedly looted. Many Albanians have lost their life savings
after the collapse of the investment funds.
</P>
<P>
So far, over 400 people have been killed in the violence.
</P>
<P>
Some 6,000 troops from an eight-nation Italian-led force have
arrived in Albania in the past two weeks to secure the delivery
of humanitarian aid.
</P>
</TEXT>
