<HEADLINE> Dalian Gives More Help to Retired Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, May 1 (Xinhua) -- This port city in northeast China's
Liaoning Province has worked out a way to guarantee the benefits
of workers retired from poorly managed state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
About 17,000 retired workers from three local state-owned
enterprise groups bade farewell to their employers yesterday, and
were handed over to a local service center, which will take care
of their social benefits, such as pensions and medical care.
</P>
<P>
The office is called the "Service Center for Retirees" and was
set up to take the heavy financial burden from state-owned
enterprises that have a large number of retired workers to take
care of.
</P>
<P>
Chen Zhenggao, deputy mayor of the city, said that this
suggests that a new social welfare system has been created in
Dalian, which will help the state-owned enterprises face
challenges from a market economy.
</P>
<P>
Official sources indicate that the total number of retired
workers under the care of the center has reached 22,000. However,
the city has a total of 300,000 retirees who need help from the
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
