<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing To Replace More Transients by Laid-Offs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 1 (Xinhua) -- About 50,000 unemployed Beijingers
are expected to obtain jobs vacated by transient workers coming
from other places by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily quoted Wang Guofang, an official with the
Beijing Labor Bureau as saying that it will be the outcome of
limiting the hiring of workers from other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Beijing municipal government has earlier adopted a regulation
to curb employment of rural job seekers for some kinds of work
that the displaced Beijingers would like to do, in an effort to
help Beijing's laid-offs to find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Job posts required to be reserved for Beijingers include such
occupations as accountants, secretaries, sales clerks, bus
conductors, waiters and elevator operators.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government also adopted other preferential
policies for the Beijing laid-offs, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
These include tuition-free education in 29 vocational schools
for the displaced workers and a work unit can receive 3,000 yuan
(361 US dollars) from the municipal government for hiring a female
displaced worker above the age of 35 and for a male over 40 if the
worker is employed for at least two years.
</P>
<P>
Quite a number of factories which employ the laid-offs will be
exempted from paying taxes during the first three years of their
operation.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has registered a total of 110,000 laid-off workers by
the end of 1996 because of the reform of the state-own
enterprises. The number is expected to raise to 200,000 this year
and the municipal government expects to help at least 60 percent
of them to find new jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
