<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Italians Favor Euro, Doubt Italy's Chance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Most Italians strongly favor the
creation of a single European currency, the euro, but have serious
doubts over Italy's chance of being the first nations to adopt the
currency.
</P>
<P>
A poll commissioned recently by the Italian weekly Panorama
showed that 67 percent of the 800 people interviewed were in favor
of creating the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
Only 16 percent of those surveyed were "not very" favorable for
and 8 percent were opposed to the EMU due to the fears of greater
unemployment, the sacrifices necessary to be part of the EMU and
the possibility of Italy playing a secondary role.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-five percent of Italians surveyed doubted Italy's chance
of being qualified for the single European currency on schedule,
while 41 percent were optimistic over its qualification. 
</P>
</TEXT>
