<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unqualified Foreign-Funded Firms Closed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 1 (xinhua) -- Fourteen percent of foreign-funded
firms in east China's Shangdong province were shut down in a
recent check.
</P>
<P>
Operation permits of 2,515 firms, with a combined contract
investment of 2.2 billion US dollars, were revoked because of
their illegal actions, such as tax evasion and chaotic financial
managment.
</P>
<P>
A lower rate of income and product exports than contracted were
also found in some firms.
</P>
<P>
According to China's law, some foreign-funded firms are asked
to export a certain percentage of their products.
</P>
<P>
The provincial foreign trade and economic cooperation
commission carried out a thorough check on the operation of 17,527
foreign-invested firms in the province recently and 86 percent
were proved to be qualified.
</P>
<P>
The shutdown of the unqualified firms will help promote the
overall level of utilization of foreign funds and ensure a stable
and healthy development of jobs, said the commission.
</P>
<P>
The commission also said that it would cooperate with other
departments to further check these firms in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Malnourished Children Decrease in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The number of children with some
degree of malnutrition in Costa Rica dropped by nearly 30 percent
between 1982-1996, a study from the Health Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The number of children under six years old with moderate or
severe malnutrition dropped from 6.3 percent in 1982 to 5.0 in
1996, and those with slight malnutrition fell from 24.6 percent to
17.3, the study said.
</P>
<P>
Other figures show an advance in better nutrition among
Costa Rican children since the number of children shorter than
they should be at their age decreased from 29.3 to 21.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Overweight children increased from 2.5 to 4.2 percent, the
study indicated.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Herman Weinstock attributed the positive
conditions to the health measures taken by the government,
including vaccination and primary health care campaigns.
</P>
<P>
But he warned that malnutrition still affects both urban and
rural children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Powers Strike Forth in World Cup Qualifiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Soccer powers recorded their
respective victories as Europe witnessed an action-packed midweek
in its World Cup qualifying tournaments on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Germany struck twice for a 2-0 victory over group leader
Ukraine, moving into the second spot with 11 points against
Ukraine's 12 points with a game in hand.
</P>
<P>
The second half goals from Oliver Bierhoff and Mario Basler
were not too late for Germany as they shrugged off the dizziness
to display their forms as three-time winners.
</P>
<P>
Italy, also three-time titlists, surged further with a
convincing win of 3-0 over Poland in Naples. Roberto Baggio,
making his first appearance for almost two years, scored the third
goal as a substitute.
</P>
<P>
Italy kept its four point lead over England which enjoyed eight
points ahead of third place Poland by beating Georgia 2-0 at
Wembley through Teddy Sheringham and Alan Shearer.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands remained atop Group Seven with a 6-0 victory at
San Marino, with three points ahead of Belgium that downed Turkey
3-1 as Luis Oliveira scored his hat-trick feat.
</P>
<P>
Romania, Group Eight leader, seemed to become the first
European qualifier by defeating Ireland 1-0 in Bucharest to keep
its winning streak in six games for an eight point advantage over
its rivals.
</P>
<P>
Sweden downed Group Four leader Scotland 2-1 but the Scots
still topped the standings with 14 points from seven games.
</P>
<P>
Denmark secured the top spot of Group One with a 4-0 victory
over Slovenia in Copenhagen with two goals from Allan Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
Overnight leader the Greeks went down 1-0 at home to Croatia
and relegated to second on goal difference.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia and Spain fought to a 1-1 tie in Belgrade in a
battle for the top spot in Group Six. Spain stays at the top with
17 points to 16.
</P>
<P>
Russia cruised to a 3-0 victory over Luxembourg and jumped into
second place with 11 points from five games, as Israel stayed atop
Group Five after scoring a 2-0 victory over Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
In another Group Four game, Latvia downed Belarus 2-0 to move
out of the cellar.
</P>
<P>
And The Faeroe Islands gained its first World Cup victory by
scoring a 2-1 win at Malta in Group Six. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
