<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai To Host French Hi-tech Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 1 (Xinhua) -- In a move to strengthen Sino-French
trade, more than 300 French companies will gather in Shanghai for
a hi-tech exposition scheduled to open on May 17 and continue
through May 21, announced French Trade Commissioner Jacques Dumasy
yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The show, known as Exposition Francaise de Hautes Technologies,
will be officially inaugurated by French President Jacques Chirac
who will be on a China visit at that time, according to today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Covering 14,000 sq. m. of floor space, the exposition will
showcase state-of-the-art French technology in the areas of
energy, space, transportation, construction and infrastructure,
telecommunications, computers, electronics, environmental
protection and health care, said Dumasy who is based in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
More than 30,000 professionals are expected to visit the show.
</P>
<P>
The French Government is subsidizing four percent of the show's
total expenses in an effort to bring French companies closer to
their Chinese counterparts, Dumasy said.
</P>
<P>
Hi-tech French companies that already have a strong presence in
China will participate in the show.
</P>
<P>
Up to 75 percent of the exhibitors are small and medium-sized
companies, organized under the various regional Chambers of
Commerce and Industries, reflecting a trend for such companies to
increasingly invest and export abroad, Dumasy said.
</P>
<P>
Of the total companies, 50 percent will be making their first
appearance in China. Seminars and lectures on energy,
telecommunications and technology transfer will be held during the
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade reached 42.7 billion francs (seven billion US
dollars) in 1996. However, this amount does not parallel Frances's
worldwide economic status. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
