<HEADLINE> Riddick Bowe Works for Cable Television </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Riddick Bowe has started his
new career in the television media after his retirement from
boxing, local TV reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Home Box Office, a cable television channel, said the
two-time heavyweight champion will work for the media outlet after
he was battered in the last two fights.
</P>
<P>
In the two fights, Bowe suffered wrongful beatings from Andrew
Golota and was plunged into sadness although he won both on
disqualifications.
</P>
<P>
He finished with a record of 40-1, with 32 knockouts.
</P>
<P>
Following the two Golota fights, Bowe was recruited in the
U.S. Marine Corps Reserves last January but left the camp only
after 10 days.
</P>
<P>
"Although my time inside the ring has come to an end, it's just
the start of an exciting and important career for me," Bowe said
in a statement released by HBO. "I am delighted to begin my new
role in the HBO family."  
