<HEADLINE> Russia's Trade With CIS States Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Russia saw a growing trade with
other former Soviet republics in 1996, with a surplus of 1.7
billion U.S dollars.
</P>
<P>
The latest issue of the business weekly "Asian Economics and
Life" published in Alma Ata reports that Russia's trade with other
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) countries chalked 29.7
billion dollars in 1996, a 5.9 percent increase over the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Russia managed a trade surplus with most of the CIS countries,
except Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan and Moldova. The three countries
recorded a trade surplus of 470 million, 420 million and 33
million dollars respectively with Russia in the year.
</P>
<P>
Machinery and equipment took up 33 percent of Russia's exports
to other CIS countries, energy products 16 percent and chemical
and oil products 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
Food and metals accounted for about half of Russia's imports
from these countries in the year, the weekly said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
