<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (55-56) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (55-56)
in a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: Under what conditions can public servants in the
British Hong Kong government directly become public servants in
the government of the Hong Kong SAR?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Public servants employed in all Hong Kong government
departments, including the police department, before the
establishment of the Hong Kong SAR may all directly become public
servants in the government of the Hong Kong SAR without any
specific conditions.
</P>
<P>
However, people who hold the posts of Secretaries and Deputy
Secretaries of Departments, Directors of Bureaus, Commissioner
Against Corruption, Director of Audit, Commissioner of Police,
Director of Immigration and Commissioner of Customs and Excise
must comply with conditions provided for by the Basic Law and be
nominated by the Chief Executive and appointed by the central
government.
</P>
<P>
Question: What benefits or pensions will the Hong Kong SAR give
to public servants who retire or leave the service?
</P>
<P>
Answer: The government of the Hong Kong SAR will pay public
servants who retire or leave the service in compliance with
regulations, including those who have retired or who have left the
service in compliance with regulations before the establishment of
the Hong Kong SAR, or their dependents, all pensions, gratuities,
allowances and benefits due to them on terms no less favourable
than before, irrespective of their nationality or place of
residence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970501.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 </DATE_TIME>
