<HEADLINE> Brazil Instists On Privatizing its Largest Mining firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso said today that his government will not change
its position on the sale of the Vale DO Rio Doce Company (CVRD),
the largest state-owned mining company in Brazil and the world.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to move ahead, we are going to continue moving
ahead calmly, with tranquility and obeying all the legal
procedures, and we are not going to stop," Cardoso said in the
presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
The president said that "people know that this path is a
constructive one."
</P>
<P>
The public sale of the Vale DO Rio Doce Company began
Tuesday in the Rio de Janeiro stock exchange, the second
biggest city in Brazil, which sparked strong protests from 5,000
Brazilian demonstrators who clashed with local military police.
The confrontation left 29 people injured, news reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Vale DO Rio Doce Company has a capital of 15 billion
dollars. In 1996 it had billings totaling five billion dollars and
600 million dollars worth of profits. 
</P>
