<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba to Launch New Care System for Elderly People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Cuba will start this year to
implement a nationwide integral system of care for the old people
in order to guarantee the elderly a high standard of living,
Osvaldo Prieto, Director of the Ibero-American Senior
Center (CITED) announced today.
</P>
<P>
With its accumulation of experience, the CITED believes it is
more advantageous to care for the elderly in their place of residence
with mutual support from the family and the community so it can
create the conditions that will prevent their disability and
facilitate a fuller old age, said Prieto.
</P>
<P>
Multidisciplinary groups, currently under training, will take
part in this project that will evaluate the needs of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
With a tendency towards an aging society, a low birthrate
and a life expectation of more than 75 years, Cuba now has one
million people over the age of 65, a figure that represents 12
percent of its population.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, Chile, Spain, the
United States, Venezuela and other countries will take part
in an International seminar on care for the elderly. The seminar
will be in Havana from May 6-9, Prieto said.
</P>
<P>
Argentina, Cuba and Uruguay are the only countries in the
region with more than 10 percent of its population over the age of
65. With implementation of birth control programs in the
region, this will also be a problem for other Latin American
countries in the future, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
