<HEADLINE> French Team Happy With Silver Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The French men's
squad, which played their first-ever team final in the World Table
Tennis Championships on Tuesday, said they were happy with a
runner-up finish behind 12-time champions China.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased with the silver medal since we have already
made histroy," said French top player and 1993 world singles
champion Jean-Philippe Gatien, who lost two games in China's 3-1
victory.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Chila got the only point for France as he nippped
China's Olympic champion Liu Guoliang in the second game.
</P>
<P>
"Since we regarded ourselves as outsiders, we had been very
relaxed throughout the tournament," said world 12th-ranked
Gatien. "Making the final was a bonus for us."
</P>
<P>
Damien Eloi, who had extended Chinese Wang Tao to 29-all in the
third game, said he played his best table tennis in the final.
</P>
<P>
"I felt so free in the second set against Wang that I got an
incredible run of five points to lead 21-20," said Eloi.
</P>
<P>
At 29-29, the 29th-ranked Frenchman played an air shot on
Wang's tricky serve and then returned into the net to concede the
match point.
</P>
<P>
"I was really nervous in the second set," Wang said after the
match. "I have never played to a score of 31-29."
</P>
<P>
"If I had won this game to make it 2-2, the final result should
have been hard to predict," said Eloi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
