<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mario Pescante Re-elected CONI President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 30 (Xinhua) -- Mario Pescante, 59, was re-elected
president of the Italian Olympic Committee (CONI) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Pescante was first elected in 1993 and his second mandate will
take him up to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Out of a total 42 votes, Pescante received all but one which
turned out to be a blank ballot as he himself did not vote in the
election.
</P>
<P>
Pescante was born in Avezzano on July 7, 1938. Taught
jurisprudence at the university level, he worked as a journalist
and started out as a sportsman in 1953 as a middle distance runner
in college.
</P>
<P>
He became secretary of the Italian mission to the 1968 Olympic
Games and to the 1971 Mediterranean Games in Smyrna.
</P>
<P>
He was elected CONI general-secretary on May 3, 1973 and held
the post in successive elections up till June 30, 1991 when he was
elected CONI president.
</P>
<P>
Since 1989 he has been general secretary of the European
Olympic Committee and he is a member of the executive board of the
World Association of Olympic Committees.
</P>
<P>
Pescante was also a founding member of the Italian National
Olympic Academy and on September 5, 1994 he was made a member of
the International Olympic Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
