<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong GDP Spurs US Dollar's Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar resumed climbing
today after a one-day dip and flirted with a 4-year high against
the yen on data that showed an unexpectedly strong surge in the
country's first-quarter economy.
</P>
<P>
The 5.6 percent increase in the gross domestic product reported
by the Commerce Department was the strongest in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the statistics increased the possibility that the
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates next month to thwart
inflationary pressure, which tends to enhance the dollar's value.
</P>
<P>
The dollar touched an intraday high of 127.13 yen, before
settling in New York at 127.06 yen, up from 126.87 yen Tuesday.
The dollar settled at 1.7303 marks, up from 1.7243 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also strengthened against the pound, which retreated
to 1.6237 U.S. dollars from 1.6316 U.S. dollars partly on the
political uncertainties created by Britain's Thursday elections.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Tuesday:
5.8300 French francs, up from 5.8120; 1.4728 Swiss francs, up from
1.4675; 1,710.00 Italian lire, up from 1,707.00; 1.3963 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.3977. 
</P>
</TEXT>
