<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Shoot Higher Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 30 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks shot higher
again today, pulling some indexes much loser to record highs.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average added 46.96 points to
7,008.99. It retreated from a 95-point gain that put the blue-chip
barometer within 20 points of record territory, but enough to
finish above 7,000 for the first time since mid-March.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Dow surged by 179 points, its second biggest
point-gain ever, on news that employment costs increased only
modestly in the first quarter. In less than three weeks, the Dow
has repaired most of the damage from a 700-point, one-month slide
from March 11's record close at 7085.16
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 556.04 million
shares, higher than 547.66 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 7.29 to 801.34,
pushing back above 800 for the first time since mid-March.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 3.32 to 416.94, the Nasdaq
composite index rose 18.13 to 1,260.76, and the American Stock
Exchange composite index rose 4.88 to 552.91.
</P>
<P>
The yielding of the bond market rose after the Commerce
Department reported that U.S. economic growth exploded at an
annual rate of 5.6 percent in the first quarter, the strongest in
a decade.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product data intensified fears that vigorous
economic activity would aggravate inflationary pressures and would
spur the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
